<HEADLINE> Indonesia Announces First Stage of Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Wednesday announced the first stage of its economic and financial
reform and restructuring in a bid to overcome the current monetary
crisis.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing held here Wednesday evening, Minister of
Trade and Industry Tunky Ariwibowo said the first stage of
economic reform was approved by the first meeting of the Economic
and Financial Resilience Council headed by President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The president asked his ministers to complete as quickly as
possible revision to the proposed government budget for 1998/99
fiscal year, said Tunky.
</P>
<P>
According to the council's meeting, the revision of the budget
should be based on the assumptions of zero percent growth, 20
percent inflation and an exchange rate stabilizing at 5,000 rupiah
per U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The council also decided to incorporate the Reforestation Fund
and the Investment Fund into the government budget and to
safeguard budget allocations for poverty alleviation, health and
basic education.
</P>
<P>
The government will immediately cancel all special tax and
customs privileges previously granted to the National Car Program
as well as all budgetary and extra-budgetary funding of the
country's aircraft project, said Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhamad
who also attended the news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Governor of Bank Indonesia Sudradjad Djiwandono said
at the news briefing that he will soon announce transparent and
equitable rules for solving liquidity and solvency problems of
private banks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has decided to lift the restrictions on the
branching of joint-venture banks and sub-branching of foreign
banks, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
The government will immediately grant Bank Indonesia autonomy
to implement an effective monetary policy, he added.
</P>
<P>
On foreign trade, the meeting decided to eliminate all import
restrictions on all new and used ships.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Minister Tunky said that from February 1,
the government will cut tariffs on all food items to a maximum of
5 percent in order to ensure the lowest cost food supplies to the
population.
</P>
<P>
"This will include all food products for human consumption and
will reduce tariffs on more than 500 items," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on all non-food agricultural items such as wool and
flax will also be reduced by 5 percent in order to reduce
production costs and increase efficiency in domestic industry, he
said.
</P>
<P>
To eliminate monopoly, all farmers and traders are allowed to
freely buy and sell cloves to and from all agents at a freely
determined market price, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
From February 1, all agents are free to import, buy and sell
all types of sugar and flour except rice which has been controlled
by the government.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto has also opened widely the field of
wholesale and retail trade through his decrees. From March 31,
1998, foreign investment firms will be able to engage in all
general wholesale or retail activities, Tunky said.
</P>
<P>
From February 1, he said, the government will remove any
restrictive marketing arrangements for cement, paper and plywood
while eliminating trade regulations in wood and rattan.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's economic and financial reform program has got firm
support from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) which agreed to
provide 23 billion U.S. dollars to the country.
</P>
<P>
Tunky said President Soeharto is working on the next stage of
program implementation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
