<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Some 50 Jordanian prisoners and detainees freed by
Iraq at the order of Iraqi President Saddam Hussein left here
Wednesday for home, the Iraq News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen cars carrying the Jordanians home made up a convoy
led by Laith Shebailat, Chairman of Jordan's Engineers Union, who
brokered the release of the group.
</P>
<P>
Other 18 Jordanians freed by Iraq decided to stay in Iraq on
their own will.
</P>
<P>
Saddam Hussein ordered the release of Jordanian prisoners in
Iraq immediately after he met Laith Shebailat, a Jordanian opposer
known for his pro-Iraqi attitudes, last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian rupiah plunged to a new record low of
12,000 against the U.S. dollar in morning trading Wednesday from
9,650/9,750 per dollar at the close session Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time that the rupiah has broken the level of
10,000 against the greenback. On January 8, the rupiah fell to
11,000 per dollar, compared with 2,400 early last July. On
Tuesday, the spot rupiah opened at 10,100/10,200 against the
dollar and closed at 9,650/9,750.
</P>
<P>
As the rupiah fell, stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange
rose 4.01 percent to close at 466.003 points.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has proposed to freeze
discussions or actions with respect to the question of
inspectors' access to presidential sites before technical
evaluation meetings have come to an end in April, said U.N. chief
arms inspector Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of overseeing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, told a news conference here on Wednesday that he "can
not or will not" agree to this proposal before the Security
Council gives him new instructions on UNSCOM's mandate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
