<HEADLINE> Pakistani Cabinet Approves Anti-Terrorism Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's federal cabinet
approved on Wednesday a plan to combat terrorism which sets out to
recover all illegal arms from citizens and ban the display of
weapons in public.
</P>
<P>
The plan asks all the people holding licenses of weapons to
deposit their arms at the offices of their respective district
magistrates.
</P>
<P>
The plan also bans the display of weapons in public with the
obvious design of threatening others.
</P>
<P>
Vowing to defeat the demon of terrorism, Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said at the cabinet meeting, "The government is determined
to maintain law and order in the country."
</P>
<P>
"We will take every possible step to carry out a vigilant
implementation of the plan as strict steps are needed to combat
terrorism," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Interior will supervise the plan to be carried
out at the provincial level. The government will conduct strict
inspections on the documents of arms and ammunition traders in the
country. Trade licenses will be canceled in case of any
discrepancy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
