<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Drops in November to Lowest in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. deficit in goods
and services trade narrowed to 8.04 billion U.S. dollars in
November, 1997, the lowest in eight months, the Commerce
Department reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the U.S. trade deficit was down 11.6
percent from a revised October figure of 9.09 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
For November, the U.S. trade deficit with Japan plunged by 28
percent to 4.2 billion dollars, also the smallest gap since June.
The deficit with China fell by 20 percent to 4.13 billion dollars,
the best showing since May, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the monthly drop, for the first 11 months of 1997,
the U.S deficit with Japan is running 17 percent ahead of the
previous year and with China is up an even bigger 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 1.05 billion dollars narrowing in the overall deficit in
November reflected a 2.3 percent decline in imports of goods and
services, which fell to 87.23 billion dollars, the lowest level in
June.
</P>
<P>
The decline was largely attributed to a 968 million dollar
decrease in crude oil imports which fell to 4.04 billion dollars,
the lowest level in 20 months. Crude oil imports by volume had
surged to an all-time high in October. The smaller November figure
reflected a big drop in volume and a smaller decline in price,
averaging 17.13 dollars per barrel as against 17.65 dollars in
October.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. exports fell by 1.3 percent to 79.20
billion dollars with declining demand for computers, computer
chips and airplanes. But exports of U.S. autos and auto parts were
up 4.8 percent to an all-time high of 11.79 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. deficit with Mexico fell by a sharp 40 percent to 884
million dollars, the smallest since January 1995 when Mexico was
forced to devalue its currency.
</P>
<P>
The deficit for the first 11 months of 1997 is running at an
annual rate of 111.4 billion dollars, slightly higher than last
year's 111 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
But economists are forecasting the trade deficit for 1998 could
widen significantly in 1998 in view of the financial crisis in
some part of Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
