<HEADLINE> Fake Notes Circulating in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- There are some forged 10,000 Kwacha
notes (about seven U.S. Dollars each note) currently circulating in
Zambia, warned Bank of Zambia here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Acting Head of Public Relations of the Central Bank, Dave Kalumba,
told the public in statement to look out for the notes with serial
number g/b 7302181 which are on the forged notes, reported The
Post.
</P>
<P>
"The notes are visibly made out of ordinary paper and have no
silver line," Kalumba was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"To distinguish the genuine notes from the forged ones, members of
the public should look out for the water mark which is missing on the
fake 10,000 Kwacha."
</P>
<P>
He said there is a similarity between the newly forged note with an
earlier one which was in circulation last year.
</P>
<P>
"Both appear to have been photocopied using colur copiers," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Kalumba said the Central Bank is carrying out a full analysis and
necessary investigations to trace the source of the fake notes.
</P>
</TEXT>
