<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate President Likely to Be Ousted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The president of the Philippine
Senate, Ernesto Maceda, is in danger of being ousted as a majority
in the Senate have allegedly signed a resolution calling for his
ouster, local television reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At least 14 members of the 24-seat Senate have reportedly
signed the resolution unseating Maceda, raising hopes that former
Senate president Neptali Gonzales could once again assume the
post, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Senate session was suspended just minutes after it was
opened Wednesday afternoon. It was not clear why the session was
suspended.
</P>
<P>
Maceda was reportedly rushed to a clinic due to high blood
pressure shortly after being informed that he was being ousted
from his post.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the Senate will resume its session and decide
the fate of Maceda Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Senator Freddie Webb, who admitted having signed the
resolution, told reporters that the plan to oust Maceda is already
"a done deal."
</P>
<P>
Webb said it was his party leader, Senator Edgardo Angara, who
initiated the move to oust Maceda. Angara was the president of the
united opposition -- the Struggle of Patriotic Filipino Masses.
</P>
<P>
Webb said the primary reason cited in the resolution is the
question of Maceda's impartiality in presiding over the joint
session of Congress which shall canvass the votes for the
presidential and vice-presidential candidates in the May
elections.
</P>
<P>
Maceda is the brother-in-law of the speaker of the House of
Representative, Jose de Venecia, who is the presidential candidate
of the ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union of Christian Democrats)
party.
</P>
<P>
Maceda resigned as chairman of the united opposition early this
month after he lost to Angara the opposition's vice presidential
candidacy in the May 1998 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports indicated that Maceda could join forces with de
Venecia in seeking the mayoral post of Manila or a congressional
seat in the House of Representatives, but the Senate president has
yet to confirm his political plans.
</P>
<P>
Although Maceda appeared to have agreed to step down, he warned
that his ouster would not help in the passage of legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
