<HEADLINE> Nile Basin Conference Ends in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nile Basin States Conference
ended here Wednesday, calling for a comprehensive strategy to
rationalize the use of Nile resources, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The conference was co-organized by the World Bank in
cooperation with the United Nations Development Program and the
Canadian International Development Agency.
</P>
<P>
Experts and technicians from 10 Nile Basin states, namely,
Egypt, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda, Rwanda, Eritrea, Burundi, Kenya,
Zaire and Ethiopia, participated in the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
The participants discussed ways of minimizing the Nile water
waste and reaching an all-round Nile basin agreement on developing
the Nile resources.
</P>
<P>
At the closing session on Wednesday, they issued a number of
recommendations, calling for "moving from the stage of planning to
that of action" in the protection and utilization of Nile.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed holding regular meetings with a view to
exchanging consultations on ways of maximize the use of the Nile
water resources.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations also urged the eradication of poverty in
the Nile Basin countries and development of the Nile area through
"equitable utilization" of the river.
</P>
<P>
But the recommendations did not touch upon the oft-debated
issue of the distribution of the Nile water among the basin
countries. The only agreement on the Nile dates back to
1959. 
</P>
</TEXT>
