<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Calls on Business Get Ready for EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) - UK companies need to get prepared
for EMU even though Britain will not be joining in the first wave,
said Adair Turner, Director-General of the Confederation of
British Industry (CBI) today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the eve of a CBI conference on the practical
implications of EMU, Turner said: "The count-down has started -
companies have only 344 days to go before EMU begins, and 1440
days before the new euro notes and coins come into use."
</P>
<P>
Turner said: "Companies need to work out the implications that
EMU and a single currency will have on the way they do business."
</P>
<P>
From 1 January 1999 business environment in the EU will be
changed, Turner said, so it is vital that companies grasp the
strategic opportunities this offers and protect themselves against
any risks.
</P>
<P>
On the legal front Turner said that it was reassuring that laws
had been passed to ensure continuity of contracts after 1 January
1999.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless companies will need to make sure that existing
contracts which run beyond 1998 do not contain any clauses which
might bring them to an end, he added.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead to the time when the UK may itself join EMU,
Turner said that companies would then need to make changes to
their company accounts, payments, payrolls, sales and marketing to
take account of the euro, all of which may involve making
significant modifications to the relevant IT program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Cause Damage in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 21 (Xinhua) -- At least 500 families
have been left homeless in the northern Mozambican province of
Cabo Delgado, due to heavy rains which have been falling since
the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
Waters from the rain are about one metre deep in the town of
Mocimboada, Radio Mozambique said today.
</P>
<P>
Many houses have been destroyed, others submerged and crops
flooded, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Other districts, such as Palma and Nangade, have been cut off
from the rest of the country, making it difficult to provide the
necessary aid to the 3000 residents of the areas.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican government officials said important roads, such as
one linking the district of Mueda to Pemba, the provincial
capital, are also at risk of being blocked by floods.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Mueda District administrator, Ambrosio
Vicente, as saying there will be no hope of a good harvest if the
rain continues in northern Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
