<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Central Bank Foresees Healthy Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Nigeria has
expressed confidence of a higher gross domestic product (GDP)
this year without exerting undue pressure on the general price
level.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria recorded a GDP growth of 3.77 percent, which fell
below the set target of 5.5 percent. This year the government
also wants the economy to grow at the rate of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the bank, Paul Ogwuma, said: "This is
possible in view of the idle manufacturing capacity that exists,
the generous fiscal incentives contained in the 1998 budget as
well as the robust level of our external reserves," the official
daily New Nigerian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The development of the manufacturing industry has been very
low in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In his report on the 1998 budget early this month, Nigerian
Head of State Sani Abacha confirmed that the growth rate
of the sector fell from 1.02 percent in 1996 to 0.72 percent last
year.
</P>
<P>
The industry only managed to make slight improvement in its
capacity utilization rate last year, from the year-earlier 32.5
percent to 33 percent, Abacha said.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to boost an overall economic recovery, the government
has provided a series of incentives, including increase in
budgeted input and abolition of excise duty imposed on domestic
industries.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves now stand at 7.7
billion U.S. Dollars, compared with 4.1 billion at the end of
1996, with its foreign debt stock cut down by one billion Dollars
last year.
</P>
<P>
All this would be favorable elements for the targeted economic
growth this year, according to the apex bank governor.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, measures for the management of liquidity on a
sustainable basis had been designed and would be implemented as
appropriate, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts noted that the rapid increasing money input,
due to the this month's release of the budgeted capital vote for
both the fourth quarter of last year and the first quarter this
year, might lead to a new round of inflation if not well managed.
</P>
</TEXT>
