<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Call for N.Irish Prison Chief to Quit Rejected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland Minister for
Prison Adam Ingram rejected on Wednesday calls for the dismissal
of the Maze jail's governor Martin Mogg.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the House of Commons, Ingram denied the MP's claims
that security was deliberately lax and said since May security has
been increased, and Mogg should stay in his post.
</P>
<P>
Mogg has admitted being "naive" in believing inmates'
assurances they were not planning attacks on each other ahead of
loyalist Billy Wright's murder.
</P>
<P>
Wright's murder by prisoners from the extreme republican Irish
National Liberation Army on December 27 touched off a wave of
sectarian revenge killings which has endangered a ceasefire called
by the major guerrilla groups in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
After two serious security lapses at the Maze over Christmas --
the escape of Irish Republican Army prisoner Liam Averill and the
murder of Loyalist Volunteer Force leader Wright, parliament
member Jeffrey Donaldson, of the main pro-British Ulster Unionist
Party, told the House of Commons on Tuesday that Mogg's position
was now untenable and he must resign quickly.
</P>
<P>
But Ingram admitted that the two incidents "have cast
considerable doubt on the effectiveness of the security
arrangements that were in operation at the prison at the time" and
had damaged public confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
