<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Task Force Sets up in Zimbabwe to Review Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government today
set up a committee of four cabinet ministers to review the recent
steep price increase of basic food commodities.
</P>
<P>
The government also declared all areas that have been affected
by on-going food riots disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which was set up after a cabinet meeting,
serves as a task force and comprises Lands and Agriculture
Minister Kumbirai Kangai, Planning Commissioner Richard Hove,
Minister Without Portifolio Eddison Zvobgo, and Minister of
Industry and Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira with the minister of
industry and commerce as its chairman.
</P>
<P>
Information, Posts and Telecommunications Minister Chen
Chimutengwende told a press briefing that the committee was
tasked with coming up with recommendations on what mechanisms to
put in place to monitor and prevent profiteering which resulted
in the recent price increases.
</P>
<P>
The committee would present its recommendations to the cabinet
next week.
</P>
<P>
''To this end the government is determined to resolve the
situation fully and as a matter of urgency to ensure that after
correcting the situation, nobody in future will be able to put up
prices of basic commodities to unjustifiable and unaffordable
levels,'' he said, stressing that the move did not mean that the
government was re-introducing price controls.
</P>
<P>
He said people and business people who had their property
damaged or looted in the riots would be assisted by the
government in repairing the properties.
</P>
<P>
The minister appealed to people in the affected areas to go
back to work and desist from being ''hoodwinked by hooligans,
arsonists and other forces who have their own political
motives.''
</P>
<P>
The minister said he was aware that an organisation called
International Socialist Organisation was coordinating the riots
but branded it as a group of ''youths'' who were being funded by
some elements bent on discrediting the government.
</P>
<P>
''White farmers and industrialists are certainly behind
this,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the issue of re-introducing a state of
emergency had not been discussed during the cabinet meeting
''since situation had improved''.
</P>
<P>
" But if the situation gets out of hand, we cannot rule the
state of emergency out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past three days, thousands of residents in the capital
of Harare, Chitungwiza and Mutare staged demonstrations in
protest against recent prices increases. They looted shops and
destroyed property, causing billions of dollars losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
