<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, January 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian rupiah crashed to an all-time low of
15,000 to the U.S. dollar Thursday morning on strong dollar demand
and growing political concerns, currency dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The spot rupiah fell into uncharted territory to more than
15,000 per dollar during the lunch break before recovering to
11,900/12,350 at the close against an opening of 12,000/13,000.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the rupiah closed at 11,300/11,600 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers the government's move to formalize the second
round of a reform program arranged by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) in exchange for a 23 billion dollar bailout package
failed to impress the market.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The NATO-led multinational Stabilization Force
(SFOR) Thursday detained a Bosnian Serb war crimes suspect in
Bosnia, the western military alliance announced here.
</P>
<P>
The war crimes suspect, identified as Goran Jelisic, has been
indicted by the International Criminal Tribunal for former
Yugoslavia for the murder of more than 16 people, torture, theft,
plunder and ordering the murder of many others.
</P>
<P>
There were no casualties sustained during the action that
resulted following the identification of Jelisic on the streets of
Bijeljina.
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Thirty-nine Cambodians, who have exiled from the
country since the factional fighting in last July, returned home
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The group, which included Buddhist Liberal Democratic Party
member Son Sann and Sam Rainsy of the Khmer Nation Party, were
escorted here from the Thai capital of Bangkok by the officials of
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and
international observers.
</P>
<P>
They were scheduled to fly back on January 14, but postponed
their plan for safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
A second group of 47 royalist FUNCINPEC members, including
several governmental officials, will return Friday, the UNHCR
official said.
</P>
<P>
about 100 exiles, including politicians, still remain abroad,
mainly in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
