<HEADLINE> Fresh Clashes Not to Affect Manila-Rebel Talks: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary
Fortunato Abat said Thursday that the recent clashes between the
military and Muslim rebels in southern Mindanao will not affect
their next round of peace talks in February.
</P>
<P>
Abat told reporters that the technical committees from the
government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
would resume talks as scheduled on February 4 in Marawi City,
capital of Lanao de Sur Province in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Abat said the recent clashes between the two sides in Buldon
Town, Maguindanao Province, will be included in the agenda of the
forthcoming peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The skirmishes occurred last week and early this week near a
major MILF stronghold not from Buldon Town, killing at least eight
MILF guerrillas and one government soldier.
</P>
<P>
Abat also said he would agree to a withdrawal at the same time
of the forces of both sides from the clash area in Buldon.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has demanded that the government troops withdraw from
some areas near Camp Abubakar, the MILF's biggest camp, in Buldon.
</P>
<P>
Abat said he agreed to the MILF's demand that the government
troops should move out from a five-kilometer radius around Camp
Abubakar. But he said the MILF rebels should also pull out of the
area.
</P>
<P>
Boasting a membership of some 12,000, the MILF is presently the
strongest anti-government force in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The MILF objects to the peace treaty signed in 1996 by Manila
and the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) and wants a separate
peace agreement with the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
