<HEADLINE> Four Nations Agree on Customs Commonality, in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
says the summit of the Interstate Council of Russia, Belarus,
Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan achieved "major breakthrough decisions."
</P>
<P>
The summit was held in the Kremlin on Thursday, Interfax News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Several agreements were signed on common customs tariffs,
standardization of excise policies, key principles of cooperation
between tax services, the formation of a transport union and
common transit terms.
</P>
<P>
The four heads of state also signed a protocol on the
simplified customs clearance of goods not meant for production or
other commercial purposes, and currency transported by individuals
across the borders of the four states.
</P>
<P>
The leaders failed to sign a draft treaty on the formation of a
common economic area which was proposed by the Kazakhstan
president.
</P>
<P>
But they agreed to set up a special expert commission to
finalize the draft by February 10 for discussion at the next
session of the council due in Minsk, the capital city of Belarus,
on April 3.
</P>
<P>
The Customs Union was established in March 1996 to streamline
customs procedures among the involved countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
