<HEADLINE> HK to Invest Heavily in Transportation Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government will spend 135 billion HK
dollars (17.3 billion U.S. dollars) in the next five years
building up a strategic transportation network in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A total of 110 billion HK dollars (14.1 billion U.S. dollars)
will be invested in three priority rail projects and another 25
billion HK dollars (3.2 billion U.S. dollars) on roads, Secretary
for Transport Nicholas Ng said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The three rail projects, namely the West Rail, the Mass Transit
 Railway's (MTR) Tseung Kwan O Extension and the Kowloon-Canton
Railway Corporation's Ma On Shan Link and Hung Hom to Tsim Sha
Tsui Extension, are under various stages of active planning and
will be completed between 2002 and 2004.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a media briefing, Ng said the government is
planning to do more in the future to work out a blueprint for the
transport infrastructure in Hong Kong for the coming decades.
</P>
<P>
"For this purpose, we are undertaking the Third Comprehensive
Transport Study to assess the overall transport needs. We are also
 embarking on the Second Railway Development Study to map out a
network for a rail system for Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
The studies are expected to be completed before the end of
1999.
</P>
<P>
A higher priority has to be given to rail transport in the long
run because of the constraint on road construction imposed by Hong
Kong's scarce land resources, Ng pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy will be to develop rail transport to the extent
that is economically viable to reduce reliance on road transport,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
