<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Seen to Remain Stable Amid Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bankers Association of the
Philippines (BAP) said Thursday that the country's currency, the
peso, will remain stable despite the pressure it gets from the
continuous fall of the Indonesian rupiah.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials admitted that the continuous plunge of the
rupiah against the U.S. dollar is a reaction to reports that there
could be political instability in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
BAP President Deogracias Vistan said there is a tendency that
the peso is not likely to plummet as expected but will hover at
around 41 to a dollar.
</P>
<P>
The peso had been strengthening against the dollar lately until
Wednesday when it dropped slightly from 40.8 to 41.9 pesos to a
dollar.
</P>
<P>
But the Philippine currency fell 2.1 percent to close at 42.79
pesos to the dollar Thursday in the Philippine official exchange
market, the Philippine Dealing System.
</P>
<P>
The peso has so far lost nearly 60 percent in its value against
the dollar since its de facto devaluation in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Vistan explained that the situation is becoming a tug-of-war of
the currencies around the region which pulls the value of the peso
to its current level.
</P>
<P>
As to the interest rates, Vistan said the Central Bank of the
Philippines has already approved the recommendation of the BAP to
open its 30-day lending window to allow banks to secure loans at a
discounted rate.
</P>
<P>
Vistan expects that this move would help a lot in strengthening
the banks' liquidity in face of the currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He said it is likely that the high interest rates will go down
to an acceptable level in the coming days as reflected by the good
economic fundamentals which are being properly managed by the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
