<HEADLINE> HK Government Not to Cut Land Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government will
 not cut back the land sales program because of the current
economic turmoil, Robert Pope, director of lands of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an annual meet-the-media session, Pope said that
since Hong Kong returned to China on July 1, the Land Department
of the SAR has been working very hard to make land available to
meet HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa's pledge of making 85,000
flats available each year.
</P>
<P>
Pope said the transition of the work of his department was
smooth as the SAR government continued most of the previous
policies on land administration after July 1.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the department executed land transactions that will
produce 45,600 flats in three to five years while the land
transactions in 1996 can produce 28,300 units, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
Pope told reporters that his department will publish its new
five-year land disposal forecast in March, which will offer a
specific land sale program for the first two financial years and
will indicate general land disposal under broad user categories
for the following three years.
</P>
<P>
As for the government's decision to withdraw the Tamar basin
site from the land auction program and to use it for the future
government headquarters, Pope said the decision has nothing to do
with the downturn of the property market.
</P>
<P>
It was a coincidence, Pope said. The government had considered
that issue for a few months and thought Tamar was an ideal site
for the future government headquarters, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
