<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Says Has No Intention to Step Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Thursday that the question of him stepping
down does not arise because the government works as a team in
tackling the country's economic woes.
</P>
<P>
"I don't hear anything about stepping down at all," Mahathir
said in response to a question by a foreign reporter as to whether
he intended to step down owing to the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government did not function on the basis of
individuality. "We are a team here. We don't function just based
on any particular individual," he said after chairing the
inaugural meeting of the National Economic Action Council (NEAC)
here.
</P>
<P>
He cited the NEAC as an example where they worked hand-in-hand
in solving problems faced by the country.
</P>
<P>
The NEAC, whose formation was announced by Mahathir on November
20, 1997, became functional Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir has been in office as Malaysia's fourth prime minister
for 17 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
