<HEADLINE> Mandela Hails Regional Cooperation at Launch of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Opening a giant project
transporting water from Lesotho mountains to South Africa, South
African President Nelson Mandela today hailed the economic
cooperation between the two countries and in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Lesotho King Letsie III today jointly opened the
huge Katse Dam at Muela in northern Lesotho, which is the heart
of the 10-billion-Rand Lesotho Highland Water Project to
alleviate the water shortage in northern South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Our joint presence here today confirms that those who shared
the trenches of struggle are today working together as free
nations to realize the possibilities of freedom," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma, Botswanan President Ketumile
Masire and South African Water Affairs Minister Kadar Asmal also
attended the ceremony of the scheme, which South African
officials say has "great economic significance" for neighboring
southern African nations in the Orange River Basin.
</P>
<P>
Under a treaty signed by South Africa's previous government
and Lesotho in 1986, the project is to pump 258 million cubic
meters a year into South Africa's north and north-east regions
for 30 years. It will save Gauteng, South Africa's industrial
heartland, from frequent drought strikes.
</P>
<P>
The success of the scheme, Mandela said, "testifies to the
powerful spirit of cooperation that is growing as Africa lifts
itself through its own efforts, with the strong support of the
international community".
</P>
<P>
He said the project will help change the lives of millions of
poor people in South Africa and Lesotho who have not had access
to clean running water.
</P>
<P>
Villages on the Lesotho highlands will also benefit from the
roads, communication services and power supply installed during
the 11 years of construction of the project, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides millions of Rand of water fees from South African
consumers, Lesotho also gets a 72-megawatt hydro-electric plant
under the project treaty, which is enough to supply all its
power needs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the international significance in completing the
project, Mandela said that it contributes to a development environmen
t
conducive to further regional cooperation in southern Africa. Endite
m

=01221440
NNNN
22:37 22:37 g # PAB
</P>
