<HEADLINE> Earthquake Caused Cracks on Great Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Many cracks have appeared on
the Great Wall because of the 6.2-magnitude earthquake that hit
Zhangjiakou in northwest China's Hebei Province on Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
"Cracks appeared on the part of the wall in Shangyi, Zhangbei
and Wanquan counties which were seriously affected by the
earthquake," He Yong, director of city Administration of Cultural
Relics, said today. "Yet there is no further damage to the wall,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
There are 2,000 kilometers of Great Wall in Zhangjiakou, which
were mainly built during the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
According to He, more than 20 ancient buildings, pagodas and
grottos are located in the quake-hit areas, mostly dating back to
the Ming Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
"All the historical sites suffered from the earthquake," He
said, "You can see cracks on them, but no further damages."
</P>
<P>
The earthquake claimed 49 lives and injured more than 10,000,
leaving 44,000 people homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
