<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Receives Bashir's Special </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today received a special message from Sudanese President Omar
Bashir delivered by Sudanese Federal Minister Ali Alhaji,
according to a Kenya News Agency report today.
</P>
<P>
No details about the message are available, but observers here
said that this is obviourly related to the incoming peace talks to be
held in April between the concerned sides of Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Foreign Minister Ali Osman Mohammad Taha reportedly
said in Rome on Tuesday that peace efforts to end his country's
civil war were gaining momentum.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that he was optimistic that talks to be
held in April in Kenya's capital of Nairobi with rebel leaders
could make significant progress.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that if the April talks have been well prepared that
definitely can help bring the civil war to an end," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Last October the seven African countries making up the
Inter-governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) brokered the
first peace talks in seven years between Khartoum government and
John Garang's Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA).
</P>
<P>
Last April, the Sudanese government signed a peace agreement
with several rebel factions to end the civil war started in 1983
which claimed more than 1.3 million lives.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA did not sign the agreement, but took part in the
October talks which produced no ceasefire but reached an
agreement to meet again in April.
</P>
<P>
From February, Kenya who is in the current IGAD chair will
engage in shuttle diplomacy among the IGAD member countries to
prepare for the April talks.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana
has said: "It is encouraging that for the first time we have
managed to get both parties to agree that they have something to
discuss."
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that he had already told both sides they
needed "a relaxation of positions and effort to move closer
together between now and April."  
</P>
