<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation Down in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Canada's annual inflation rate
continued to fall in December to 0.7 percent, Statistics Canada
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This was the lowest 12-month change in the Consumer Price
Index since January 1995 when a 0.6 percent increase was posted,"
the government agency said.
</P>
<P>
The drop in rate from 0.9 percent to 0.7 percent rate was
mainly attributed to the price declines of gasoline, air travel
and cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
For the year of 1997, the average inflation rate was 1.6
percent, the same as in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Canada's inflation rate has remained low and steady since 1992,
ranging from 0.2 percent in 1994 to 2.1 percent in 1995. These
increases were the smallest since the early 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
