<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Inflation Drops in First Half of 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's inflation
registered a fall during the first six months of the current
fiscal year starting July 1, according to a report released by the
State Bank of Pakistan (SBP) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The trends in the country's economy in 1997-98 indicate a mixed
performance, the SBP said in the report on Pakistan's Economy
submitted to parliament.
</P>
<P>
The report said all available indicators of inflation show a
considerable slowdown in prices in the first half of the fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Indicator (CPI) slipped down to 6.3 percent
during July-December 1997 compared to 8.2 percent recorded a year
earlier, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said if the past pattern of distribution of
inflation between the first half and second half of the year is
maintained, the yearly inflation target of 9.0 percent may be
achieved as compared with 11.8 percent in 1996-97 and the average
of 11.3 percent in the last 5 years.
</P>
<P>
Several factors have contributed to the moderation in
inflation, the most important being a slowdown in the rate of
credit expansion due to both lower government borrowing and
moderation in expansion of credit to the private sector, it said.
</P>
<P>
The SBP report also points out a decline in the Wholesale Price
Indicator (WPI) and Sensitive Price Indicator (SPI) during the
first half of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The WPI was recorded at 5.1 percent during July-December 1997
as compared to 9.3 percent during the corresponding period of
1996, whereas the SPI stood at 6.2 percent as against 8.8 percent
during the first three months of 1996-97, it said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank report also said the trade deficit narrowed to
1.08 billion dollars during July-December 1997, compared with 1.72
billion dollars in the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The deficit on current account of the balance of payments, for
which data are available only for July-November 1997, also
narrowed remarkably, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
