<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate President Forced to Step Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- President of the Philippine
Senate Ernesto Maceda said Thursday that he has agreed to step
down as called for by a majority of his fellow colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Maceda, who became Senate president in October 1996, is
scheduled to hand over his post to former Senate head Neptali
Gonzales next Monday when the Senate resumes its session.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a closed-door Senate meeting,
Maceda said he accepted the decision of the majority of the Senate
"without rancor or regrets."
</P>
<P>
Maceda also "congratulated" Vice President Joseph Estrada and
Senator Edgardo Angara, both leaders of the United Opposition, on
"masterminding and successfully achieving" his ouster.
</P>
<P>
But his congratulations were quickly dismissed by Estrada who
bluntly denied his involvement in the Senate coup.
</P>
<P>
Maceda also said his blood pressure had already returned to
normal and he was in "very good health."
</P>
<P>
Maceda was rushed to a clinic Wednesday afternoon because his
blood pressure shot up shortly after being informed that he was
being ousted from his post.
</P>
<P>
Maceda's agreement to stand down came one day after he was
informed by some senators that at least 16 members of the 24-seat
Senate, most of them from the United Opposition, had signed a
resolution calling for his step-down.
</P>
<P>
But the resolution has not yet been publicized by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the senators questioned in the resolution
Maceda's impartiality in presiding over the joint session of the
Philippine Congress, which shall canvass votes for the
presidential and vice-presidential candidates in the May
elections.
</P>
<P>
Maceda is the brother-in-law of the speaker of the House of
Representative, Jose de Venecia, who is the presidential candidate
of the ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union of Christian Democrats)
party.
</P>
<P>
But what was really behind Maceda's ouster was his breakaway
from the United Opposition and his political rivalry with Angara,
political observers said.
</P>
<P>
Maceda resigned as chairman of the United Opposition early this
month after he lost to Angara the opposition's vice presidential
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports indicated that Maceda could join forces with de
Venecia in seeking the mayoral post of Manila or a seat in the
House of Representatives, but the Senate president has yet to
confirm his political plans.
</P>
<P>
Gonzales, who was forced to turn over the Senate presidency to
Maceda in October 1996 in a similar Senate coup, will take over as
the head of the Senate Monday for a third time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
