<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Stresses Land Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Vice Premier Zou Jiahua said
here today that the country should maintain the total amount of
arable land and stop illegal use of farm areas.
</P>
<P>
Zou made his remarks at an ongoing national meeting on land
management. He encouraged locals to develop more arable land
through all kinds of means.
</P>
<P>
A national check on land resources has shown that during the
1991-1996 period, 116,500 hectares of arable land lay idle and
there were 3.8 million cases of violation against land law.
</P>
<P>
Half of the cases have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
China has to support 22 percent of world's population with
one-seventh of the world's arable land. 
