<HEADLINE> Nepal Gets ADB Loan for Agriculture Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Thursday approved a 50 million U.S. dollar concessional loan to
help Nepal with its agriculture sector reforms.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used for Nepal's Second Agriculture Program
which includes a medium-term strategy focusing on better
allocation of resources and the deregulation of the fertilizer
market, the ADB said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Sustainable agricultural growth is a prerequisite to economic
development and poverty reduction in Nepal, said the Manila-based
bank, adding that agriculture accounts for 42 percent of Nepal's
gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Nepal's agriculture sector, however, is constrained by public
interventions, including subsidies, which have long stifled
private initiatives and generated market distortions, the ADB
said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB-funded program will help deregulate the agriculture
sector and promote private sector participation in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The loan will come from the bank's concessional Asian
Development Fund, which is interest-free.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
