<HEADLINE> Electronic Commerce Promoted in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Manufacturers'
Association of Hong Kong (CMA) and Tradelink Thursday signed an
agreement to promote the use of electronic commerce in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the CMA will hold a series of marketing
activities and seminars to encourage the use of Tradelink's
electronic commerce services by the association's 3,800 member
companies, almost all of which are manufacturers or import/export
traders.
</P>
<P>
Tradelink, a private company in which the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government is a major shareholder,
provides two current ranges of electronic commerce services for
Hong Kong's trading community -- SilkNet for garment and textile
traders and ValuNet for general importers and exporters.
</P>
<P>
The services allow exporters and manufacturers to apply to the
government for textile export licenses and lodge their trade
declarations electronically, bringing savings in time and cost,
and enhancements in efficiency and productivity.
</P>
<P>
CMA President Herbert Liang, addressing the signing ceremony,
said the use of electronic commerce can help Hong Kong exporters
and manufacturers minimize human errors and increase efficiency in
a streamlined operation, and maintain their competitiveness in
world markets through effective monitoring of labor cost.
</P>
<P>
Tradelink Chief Executive Officer Justin Yue said the
partnership with the CMA, one of Hong Kong's largest trade
associations, will play an important role in spreading the message
about electronic commerce and its benefits.
</P>
<P>
"If Hong Kong is to stay competitive in world markets, it's
essential that electronic commerce becomes widely adopted within
the next three years," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
