<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hongkong Telecom Gets New Antenna for Wider Coverage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Hongkong Telecom has recently
installed a new antenna to match the operation of a satellite
called APSTAR-2R as a key step to allow broadcasters a much wider
coverage across the globe.
</P>
<P>
The satellite antenna, named HK 18, will enable broadcasters to
explore and reach new markets in Asia, Europe, Africa and
Australia. Operating hand-in-hand with the APSTAR-2R equipped with
28 C-Band transponders, the new nine-meter C-Band antenna can
ensure high-capacity and superb-quality data and video
transmission.
</P>
<P>
HK 18 will be monitored all day and all year round as all the
other antennae placed at Hongkong Telecom's Stanley Earth
Stations, Asia's largest and most extensive commercial teleport.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Telecom's manager for broadcast and fixed satellite
services K. W. Chan said Thursday: "As one of the world's leading
satellite service providers, Hongkong Telecom is committed to
employing the latest technologies to meet customers' growing
demand for quality, coverage and reliable services. The
commissioning of HK 18 is proof of this continuing commitment."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is strategically located for access to key local,
regional and international satellite systems. Hongkong Telecom has
been taking advantage of Hong Kong's geographic position to
provide satellite services to broadcasters for nearly three
decades.
</P>
<P>
APSTAR-2R is one of the APSTAR series of satellites launched by
Asia Pacific Telecommunications Satellite Co. Ltd. (APT), a
leading satellite company in the Asia-Pacific region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
