<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Has No Liquidity Problems: Mahathir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad denied Thursday that his country is facing
liquidity problems this year.
</P>
<P>
"We have enough liquidity. Liquidity is at 490 billion ringgit
(about 109 billion U.S. dollars) currently and there shouldn't be
a problem in getting loans," Mahathir told reporters after
chairing the first meeting of the National Economic Action Council
(NEAC) here.
</P>
<P>
On claims that the country is facing liquidity problems,
Mahathir said there is a misunderstanding that companies found it
difficult getting loans.
</P>
<P>
In fact those finding it difficult to get loans are companies
involved in the non-productive areas, he said, adding that the
government has directed banks to focus on lending to productive
sectors like manufacturing and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Thursday's meeting identified several areas with
focus on ensuring liquidity in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
Several suggestions were made Thursday on how to overcome
liquidity problems if they arose, he said, adding, "But none had
been finalized, I cannot disclose it."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said there is no need to bail out companies despite
the current economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would not be protecting anybody. "If
they have legitimate reasons, we will have to look at them ...
There is no question of a bail-out," he added.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the NEAC was announced by Mahathir on November
20 last year to chart strategies to tackle economic problems
facing the country following the collapse of local currency and
stock markets in the wake of a regional financial crisis that
began in Thailand last July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
