<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Keeps World's Third Biggest Foreign Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The foreign reserves of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) stood at 92.8
billion HK dollars at the end of 1997, keeping third place in the
world after Japan and China's inland, the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the end of December 1997, the official foreign currency
assets vested in the Exchange Fund were 75.3 billion US dollars,
while those held in the Land Fund were 17.5 billion US dollars,
the HKMA said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign reserves reached 96.5 billion US dollars at the end
of November 1997. An HKMA spokesman attributed the drop in
December to falling Hong Kong dollar interest rates in the month.
</P>
<P>
Short-term capital was attracted to the Hong Kong dollar by
jacked-up interest rates in November, pushing the foreign currency
assets to a record high.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's foreign reserves are about 10 times the currency in
circulation, one of the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the world's largest foreign reserves holder with
220.8 billion US dollars at the end of 1997, while China's inland
areas ranked second with 139.9 billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
