<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rupiah Hits new low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah crashed
to an all-time low of 15,000 to the U.S. dollar Thursday morning
on strong dollar demand and growing political concerns, currency
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The spot rupiah fell into uncharted territory to more than
15,000 per dollar during the lunch break before recovering to
11,900/12,350 at the close against an opening of 12,000/13,000.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the rupiah closed at 11,300/11,600 per dollar.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers the government's move to formalize the second
round of a reform program arranged by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) in exchange for a 23 billion dollar bailout package
failed to impress the market.
</P>
<P>
They said the rupiah sagged further on reports that Indonesian
corporations were resorting to rupiah payments for their U.S.
dollar debts.
</P>
<P>
More and more private companies and banks have settled their
offshore obligations with rupiah, prompting offshore parties to
cover short dollar positions, the dealers said.
</P>
<P>
"This situation has forced local banks to buy dollars at any
level today as they are afraid foreign players, with excess
rupiah, will kick the currency down further," a local bank dealer
said.
</P>
<P>
According to a government estimate, the offshore debt of the
Indonesian private sector was 65 billion U.S. dollars as of
September last year. Most of the loans were short-term debts with
a maturity of between one and two years.
</P>
<P>
But the main negative factor seemed to be the announcement by
House Speaker Harmoko Tuesday that the candidate for the next vice
president must have a vision on science and technology, and deep
knowledge of industry and its usage.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto confirmed Tuesday that he would seek a
seventh five-year term in March.
</P>
<P>
Another factor for the fall of rupiah was the weakness of
regional currencies including Malaysian Ringgit, Singapore dollar,
Thai baht, the Philippine peso and South Korean won.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the stock prices on the Jakarta Stock Exchange also
fell by 4.8 percent or 22.474 points to close at 443.529 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
