<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Worse than expected quarterly
results, continuing Asian fears and a slump in National Australia
Bank (NAB) shares pushed the Australian share market lower
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds &AMP; Co. broker Grant Williamson said that while the
day-to-day trend was getting harder to pick, the local bourse
started its slide Wednesday with ANZ bank's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The ANZ (meeting) got people thinking about their exposure to
Asia ... that's pushed stocks down a bit," he said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said Wednesday that the Asian crisis would inevitably
see an increase in the level of assets recognized as impaired
throughout the region. ANZ estimated that its total provisioning
charge this financial year would climb from pre-tax 240 million
U.S. dollars to pre-tax 320 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Williamson said the market was also lower because investors
were easing off with the Australia Day long weekend coming up.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed down 23.4 points to 2599.4
while the All Industrials Index dropped by 44.8 points to 4479.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, National Australia Bank shares shed 38
cents to close at 20.75 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank said Thursday that its first-quarter net profit fell
10 percent to 334 million U.S. dollars from 372 million dollars,
hit by an increase in provisioning for doubtful debts.
</P>
<P>
One broker said the NAB results were worse than expected.
</P>
<P>
ANZ shares dropped 17 cents to 9.8 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other banking stocks were also weaker, with Westpac 12.2 cents
down at 10.17 Australian dollars and Commonwealth Bank closing
steady at 18.5 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index dropped 5.8 points to 1096.6.
</P>
<P>
Shares of Australia's three major iron ore producing companies
-- BHP, Rio Tinto and North Ltd. -- were higher mid-morning
following news that they had achieved a price rise in the sales
agreements with Japanese steel mills.
</P>
<P>
But only Rio and North managed to hang onto their earlier
gains, closing up 35.2 and 7 cents at 18.95 and 4.07 Australian
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
BHP ended 7 cents down at 13.65 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 234.00 million shares worth 496.2 million
U.S. dollars with falls outnumbering rises by 609 to 437.
</P>
</TEXT>
