<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maps Out Anti-Corruption Guidelines in 1998 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China has mapped out the
guidelines for its anti-corruption drive in 1998, under the
guidance of Deng Xiaoping Theory and the guidelines of the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
The guidelines were set forth at the second plenary session of
the CPC Central Commission for Discipline Inspection held in
Beijing from January 20-22. Attending the session were 112 members
of the Commission and leading officials from discipline inspection
departments of central and local departments, according to a
communique issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The session urged the whole party to deeply understand the
great significance of combating corruption in the process of
reform, opening up and modernization drive based on the reality of
the primary stage of socialism, and to increase efforts in
checking the trend of spreading of corruption, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
"We must both crack down on corruption cases that has already
happened, and prevent and curb corruption from its very source,"
the communique said, adding that the anti-corruption drive should
start from leading departments and officials by increasing
management and supervision on leading officials at all levels.
</P>
<P>
According to the guidelines, the requirements for the
anti-corruption drive in 1998 include:
</P>
<P>
-- Concerning the self-discipline of leading officials, strict
controls must be put on building and indoor fitting-up of office
buildings and on holding all kinds of meetings and celebrations.
Leading officials are forbidden to use public fund to hold
banquets, install household phones or purchase mobile phones, and
must use or change cars strictly according to regulations;
</P>
<P>
-- With regard to the investigation of major cases, stress must
be put on cases involving leading officials, and corruptive
officials must be punished seriously;
</P>
<P>
-- As for checking unhealthy tendencies, the focus must be put
on alleviating the burdens of farmers and enterprises and on
clearing up extra-budget funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maps Out Anti-Corruption Guidelines in 1998 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The year of 1998 is an important and crucial year, the
communique says, and leading officials at all levels, especially
high- and middle-ranking officials, should guarantee the execution
of the policy decisions worked out at the 15th CPC National Congress
which was held last September.
</P>
<P>
It emphasized that the anti-corruption drive should focus on
the following aspects:
</P>
<P>
-- Increasing education of Party members in the Party spirit,
the Party's style of work and discipline by popularizing the
education of the Party's own regulations, and state laws and
regulations in a planned way;
</P>
<P>
-- Improving the legal system to ensure the orderly execution
of the fight against corruption for a clean government;
</P>
<P>
-- Intensifying internal supervision of the Party by
establishing a mechanism to guarantee that power is exercised
according to laws, and increasing democratic supervision, and
popularizing in rural China the open and democratic operation of
village affairs;
</P>
<P>
-- Deepening the reform to reduce and eliminate the conditions
for breeding corruption.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, General Secretary of the CPC Central Committee,
made an important speech at the session. Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Zhu
Rongji, Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing, Li Lanqing, and other
Party and state leaders also attended the session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
