<HEADLINE> East China City Becomes Large Collectors Market By Chen Yao, Liu Meijun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- On weekends, more and more
collectors of fine arts and antiques flock to collection markets
in Hangzhou -- a historic cultural city in east China.
</P>
<P>
Hangzhou, capital of Zhejiang Province and famous for its
picturesque West Lake, has grown into possibly the third largest
market after Shanghai and Nanjing for such collectibles as stamps,
antiques, paintings, phone cards, china, coins, paper money and
old-style furniture.
</P>
<P>
So far, five permanent distribution markets for collectibles
have been established in the city with more than 1,200 shops and
stands.
</P>
<P>
The largest of the five is a newly opened stamp market, which
occupies more than 4,000 square meters. Its daily trade volume
reaches into several million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In Wulin Square in the city's central business district, a
monthly folk collection trade fair attracts 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey, stamps have the largest market
share in collectibles followed by phone cards, coins, paper money
and antiques.
</P>
<P>
In the Wulin Stamp Market in Hangzhou, one trader said: "I can
sell 100,000 yuan (12,000 U.S. dollars) in one day."
</P>
<P>
Chinese have a long tradition of collecting paintings and
antiques during times of peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"I have been involved in selling antiques for three years,"
said Li Jianhua, a trader who graduated from the department of
Chinese Language and Literature at Hangzhou University. "In this
business, it is really true that `knowledge is money'."
</P>
<P>
To improve their knowledge, the city's collectors have formed
specialized associations such as the Hangzhou Stamp Association
and the Hangzhou Coin Association.
</P>
<P>
Lu Longchang, a collector, has even started a publication named
"Spring and Sea" about coin-collecting, which reports market
information.
</P>
<P>
To regulate the distribution, Hangzhou has increased its
administrative controls over collection markets. According to a
local legislator, the city is drafting new rules to standardize
the markets' operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
