<HEADLINE> Australian Open Courts Inhumane: Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Open tennis
courts again came in for criticism from players Wednesday with one
of the tour's most respected players describing them as "inhumane".
</P>
<P>
Todd Martin, a finalist in Melbourne in 1994, said the courts
were too hard on players' feet, especially on a hot day, the
Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
With the centre court temperature reaching 40 degrees Wednesday,
the Rebound Ace surface took its toll on players, it added.
</P>
<P>
Martin said his feet were bleeding after the match.
</P>
<P>
"These courts ... it's inhumane what they do to our feet," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Last year players complained bitterly about the courts as air
temperatures soared and the court surface temperature rose to more
than 60 degrees.
</P>
<P>
The Rebound Ace surface consists of a thin rubberised compound
spread over a concrete base.
</P>
<P>
It is similar to other hardcourt surfaces such as that used at
the US Open.
</P>
<P>
But on a hot day the rubber coating can become slightly tacky
and players moving at high speed and then stopping sharply risk
injury when their shoes stick.
</P>
<P>
They also suffer severe blistering because their feet move
inside their shoes when the sole sticks to the court.
</P>
<P>
Martin's opponent Pat Rafter, who was treated at courtside
today for bruising to his foot, said the courts could become
difficult in hot weather, but they were not much different to
other hardcourt surfaces, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the tournament other players said their shoes were
sticking to the surface, with Frenchman Guillaume Raoux suffering
severe blistering.
</P>
<P>
Before the Open started, Andre Agassi complained that it was
"38 percent slower" than last year.
</P>
<P>
Tournament director Paul McNamee said the surface was slightly
slower than that on which Agassi won the Open in Melbourne in
1995, but was faster than last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
