<HEADLINE> Bombs Left by Gulf War Defused in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Civil defense teams in Iraq's
province of Salladin, 180 kilometers north of Baghdad, have
defused 8,696 bombs left over by the 1991 Gulf War, the Iraqi News
Agency (INA) said.
</P>
<P>
Civil defense teams in Iraq's province of Najaf, 170 kilometers
south of Baghdad, have also defused 47 bombs and missiles left by
the war without suffering any damages or casualties, the agency
added.
</P>
<P>
According to INA, the anti-Iraq coalition aircraft dropped 881
missiles and bombs over the city of Najaf during the Gulf War in
1991, killing 107 citizens, injuring 165 others and damaging a
number of residential buildings and places of worship.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf War was triggered by Iraqi aggression of Kuwait in
1990. Iraq was defeated and driven out of Kuwait by the U.S.-led
coalition forces after months of occupation. 
</P>
