<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined sharply
on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index fell by 3.2 percent, or 41.91 points, to close at 1269.49 on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said prices fell on worries over a persistent plunge in
the Indonesian rupiah, which had taken a toll on other regional
currencies. Trading was dull as people were sidelined by the
falling regional currencies, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that there was some buying interest
absorbing the fall while property stocks were hardest hit over
concerns that higher interest rates would dent affordability.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank further to 210.65 million units,
valued at 375.1 million Singapore dollars (about 213.13 million
U.S. dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 268 to 77 while
264 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Technologies Engineering was the most actively
traded counter as it registered a turnover of 15.01 million units.
It was followed by Singapore Telecom which had 11.73 million
shares traded. TAC 200 was next with 8.91 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 60 cents to finish at 33.4 Singapore
dollars. KepFELS and the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) increased
by 30 cents each to end at 4.7 and 16.3 Singapore dollars
respectively. Gentings was up by 10 cents to close at 4.22
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign
and Yeo HSS shared the top spot on the losers' list as each of
them declined by 60 cents to end at 11.3 and 5 Singapore dollars
respectively. City Developments fell by 55 cents to close at 5.65
Singapore dollars while the Singapore Airlines (SIA) Foreign
dropped by 50 cents to finish at 11 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
