<HEADLINE> U.S. Minister Cautions S.Korea Against Defense Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of
Defense William Cohen said here Thursday that any cut in South
Korea's defense budget could raise tensions on the Korean
Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"I believe any reduction (of the defense budget) at this time
would send the wrong signal and enhance and escalate tension on
the Korean Peninsula," Cohen told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said his country hopes South Korea will recognize this and
maintain the same level of commitment.
</P>
<P>
The original defense budget of 14.6 trillion won (about 8.9
billion U.S. dollars) for this year will be reduced by 1.35
trillion won (about 810 million dollars), almost 10 percent. This
is because of the financial crisis caused by the bankruptcy of
conglomerates and bad loans by financial institutions since late
1997.
</P>
<P>
However, owing to the won's sharp devaluation against the
U.S. dollar, the budget cut is expected to amount to the
equivalent of over three trillion won (about 1.8 billion
dollars). The South Korean won depreciated more than 50 percent in
the past few months.
</P>
<P>
South Korea originally planed to buy C-17 transport airplanes,
early warning aircraft, coastal radar systems and other weapons.
</P>
<P>
Over the country's request to reduce payments for supporting
the 37,000 U.S. troops here, Cohen said experts from both
countries will discuss the matter in light of the South Korean
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has no intention of taking advantage or
profit off South Korea's economic crisis," said Cohen, who
finished the last leg of his seven-nation Asian tour Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit, Cohen has met President Kim
Young-sam, President-elect Kim Dae-jung and Defense Minister Kim
Dong-jin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
