<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Banks Lose 2.2 Billion U.S. Dollars in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen of South Korea's 26
commercial banks registered combined net losses of 3.9 trillion
won (about 2.2 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, in sharp contrast to
the previous year's net profit of 939 billion won.
</P>
<P>
The Office of Bank Supervision attributed the huge losses to
vast non-performing loans of financial institutions and the
bearish Seoul stock market in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The failure of a slew of big conglomerates, including Hanbo,
Kia, Jinro and Halla groups, forced commercial banks to jack up
reserve for loan losses sharply to 3.34 trillion won last year.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the depressed stock market forced the banks to
put aside no less than 2.22 trillion won as reserves to cover
book-value losses of their stock holdings.
</P>
<P>
Of the 18 banks, six are big Seoul-based ones, whose combined
losses amounted to 3.33 trillion won in 1997, accounting for 85
percent of total losses in the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Korea First Bank was the biggest loser, suffering a net loss of
1.61 trillion won, followed by Seoul Bank with 916.6 billion won,
Cho Hung Bank with 289.6 billion won, Hanil Bank with 280.9
billion won, Commercial Bank of Korea with 163.9 billion won, and
Korea Exchange Bank with 68.4 billion won.
</P>
<P>
However, the Housing &AMP; Commercial Bank raked in the largest net
profit of 108.3 billion won in 1997, up 17.4 percent from the 92.2
billion won recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Kookmin Bank got a net profit of 104.4 billion won in 1997 net
profit, followed by Shinhan Bank with 53.3 billion won, Hana Bank
with 43.5 billion won, Pusan Bank with 19.8 billion won, Daegu
Bank with 15.2 billion won, Boram Bank with 10.2 billion won, and
Kyongnam Bank with 2.9 billion won. 
</P>
