<HEADLINE> World Cup Ends on High Note with Fresh World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Cup short-course
swim meet ended on a high note in Sydney on Thursday as local hero
Michael Klim twice smashed 100 meters butterly world record within
eight hours on the day.
</P>
<P>
Klim shattered the 51.16 seconds world short-course record
which he set in the morning with a time of 51.07 eight hours later
in the afternoon,
</P>
<P>
In other World Cup finals Thursday, Russian star Alexander
Popov was upset in the 50-m freestyle, finishing second to Mark
Foster of Britain.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Katrin Meissner won the women's 100-m freestyle in
54.31 seconds.
</P>
<P>
World championship silver medalist Helen Denman of Australia
prevented her teammate Sam Riley from scoring a hatrick in
breaststroke event when she beat her in the 50-m.
</P>
<P>
Riley later won the 200-m breaststroke in 2:23.14, ahead of
Belgium's Brigitte Becue in a repeat of Wednesday night's 100
result.
</P>
<P>
World championship 1,500-m silver medalist Emiliano Brembill of
Italy won the 800-m in 7:39.30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
