<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Snow Hits East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A heavy snowfall rarely seen
over the past decade hit the northern part of east China's
Zhejiang province this morning, when the area has just experienced
a rare warm winter.
</P>
<P>
The snow gave no sign of abating at sunset. According to the
provincial meteorological station, it is the heaviest snowfall in
Zhejiang this year.
</P>
<P>
By three p.m. today, the accumulation of snowfall reached ten
centimeters at Lin'an, and more than eight centimeters in downtown
Hangzhou and Deqing.
</P>
<P>
Around the scenic West Lake in Hangzhou, workers have put coal
cinder on the road, and used high-pressure water pipes to remove
snow from trees to prevent them from breaking more trees.
</P>
<P>
Some of the highways connecting Hangzhou and the northeast part
of the province has been closed because of the snow.
</P>
<P>
The active flows of warm and wet currents over Zhejiang have
caused the heavy snow, meteorological specialists here explained.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang, like other provinces in east China, was experiencing
a rare warm winter with the average temperature at six to seven
degrees Celsius until two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the influence of a strong cold front, said the
specialists, the average temperature then dropped below zero
degree Celsius, and the lowest were recorded at minus six to minus
seven degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural experts expect the snowfall to cause losses to
farmers, since crops here are not prepared for the freezing
temperature following the snow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
