<HEADLINE> German Company Eyes Chinese Telecommunications Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Siemens, the German company
which sliced 20 percent of the Chinese telecommunications market
last year, expects to continue being bullish about the world's
biggest market.
</P>
<P>
That was the message today from Wolfgang Sesselmann, a senior
sales manageer of Siemens, who addressed a company sales
conference in Beijing. The company has set a target of increasing
the annual sales volume in the Chinese telecommunications market
to 815 million U.S. dollars by 2000, Sesselmann said.
</P>
<P>
Konrad Seitz, German ambassador to China, emphasized the
importance of expanding and fruitful relations between China and
his country in his speech to the conference.
</P>
<P>
"Though we came late, we have a good reputation; we believe we
will become stronger and more successful in this promising
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Known as the second biggest company in Germany with a 150-year
history, Siemens set up its first office in China 95 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 top managers of Siemens in Germany and high-ranking
representatives from branches in 16 Asian countries attended the
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
