<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Increase Assistance to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government plans
to provide more assistance to Indonesia in its coming fiscal year,
a senior official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the current 1997/98 fiscal year (ending on March 31), Japan
gave Indonesia 20 billion yen as part of the 5.3 billion U.S.
dollar soft loans provided by the Consultative Group for
Indonesia, Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said after a meeting
between visiting special envoy Masahiko Komura of the Japanese
prime minister and President Soeharto here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Komura, who is also vice foreign minister, arrived here
Wednesday at the head of a senior officials delegation.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese envoy also handed over a letter from Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to President Soeharto during the
meeting, said Moerdiono.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese prime minister hoped that Indonesia would strictly
implement the economic and financial reform program it has signed
recently with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in a bid to
overcome the monetary crisis, Moerdiono added.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also expressed his belief that under the leadership
of President Soeharto and with the implementation of the program,
Indonesia's economy could recover and this would also be conducive
to economic and monetary recovery in the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto told the Japanese guest that Indonesia will fully
implement the Indonesia-IMF agreement.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the most important thing at the movement is how
to restore public and international confidence in the rupiah, the
country's currency, which has plunged by more than 200 percent
against the U.S. dollar since July last year.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto also hoped the Japanese government would help
Indonesia increase its non-oil and gas exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Reduce Dependence on Foreign Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's reliance on
foreign military equipment will be reduced by using suitable
locally-manufactured equipment, Malaysian Defense Minister Syed
Hamid Albar said.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said at a naval base Wednesday night that the armed
forces have depended heavily on foreign equipment and the time has
come for Malaysia to use the locally produced, the national news
agency Bernama reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the present economic situation, focus should be made on the
support industries to produce components for the armed forces like
spare parts, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to Syed Hamid, Malaysia has the basics in producing
military equipment like the Styer rifle, which could be enhanced
to produce powerful equipment with greater capabilities.
</P>
<P>
He said all maintenance work for naval ships and military
aircraft was being carried out in the country.  
</P>
