<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Using Technology To Maintain Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Pan Guoqing, the director of
the Public Security Bureau in the city of Suzhou, in eastern
China's Jiangsu Province, no longer needs to bother shuffling
through a stack of files on his desk every morning, instead he
just turns on his computer and begins tracking a case.
</P>
<P>
Pan says the local police now have guidelines for maintaining
order in society by combining manpower with new
technology. Setting up the '110 police emergency line' using the
new technology will be a major way to improve the effectiveness of
the police in dealing with crimes, he explained.
</P>
<P>
When an emergency call comes in to the public security bureau,
it only takes a few key words to allow the operator get a fix on
the place where the crime has been committed on a computer screen,
meaning the police can be at the site in five to ten minutes.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the city's police got 25,000 emergency calls, 1,000 of
them involving criminal activity, 5,000 involving social disorder,
5,000 involving traffic problems, and 4,000 of them various calls
for help.
</P>
<P>
Pan says that police stations in busy areas frequently send
information in to headquarters, and 4,200 commercial outlets in
the banking and tax sectors, and large department stores and
jewelery stores are hooked up to the computer's alarm
system. Police officers can therefore be ordered to respond
immediately whenever an emergency occurs.
</P>
<P>
He says the city now has some 739 residential areas provided
with advanced security equipment. A recent survey showed that 98
percent of the residents of Suzhou are satisfied with the order,
and the 2,000-year-old city is still regarded as a kind of
"paradise" because of its good natural conditions and a high
living standard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
