<HEADLINE> German Chemical Industry Not to Reduce Investment in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, January 22 (Xinhua) -- German chemical producers
will not reduce their investment in southeast Asia despite the
current financial turmoil in the region, the German Association of
Chemical Industry said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, Germany's large chemical producers could
even move to attach much more importance to investment in
southeast Asia in the coming years, said the association president
Hans-Dietrich Winkhaus.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current crisis, southeast Asian economies would
still grow faster than other regions, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to Winkhaus, German chemical industry had a good year
in 1997, with total sales growing by 7.5 percent to 188.3 billion
marks (102.3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The boom was mainly driven by exports, which rose 12.4 percent
to 116 billion marks (63 billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, German chemical sales in home market totalled
67.1 billion marks (36.5 billion dollars) last year, representing
a rise of 9.1 percent, Winkhaus said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
