<HEADLINE> Changing China's Fixed-Assets Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China's investment in fixed
assets is changing in a positive way because of changes in the
economic structure, according to Song Mi, a State Statistics
Bureau official.
</P>
<P>
He says the country put 30.66 billion yuan (3.83 billion
U.S. dollars) into agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry,
fisheries, and water conservancy during the January-November
period of 1997. This was an increase of 56.5 percent over the same
period in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
China's western region showed strong growth during that period,
when fixed assets investment surged 22.4 percent. Fixed assets
investment in central and eastern regions grew 11.5 percent and
10.8 percent respectively, Song says.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of funds used by the energy industry, transport, and
telecommunications to the total investment during the same period
was 39.9 percent, up from 37.3 percent in 1996. Spending on the
energy industry was up 23.8 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
