<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Urged to Do Better in Foreign Exchange Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese banks in this
financial center of China were urged today to improve their
ability in dealing in foreign exchange business.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Mao Yingliang, president of the Shanghai
branch of the People's Bank of China, the central bank, at an
annual municipal meeting on financial work.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that a leading central bank official here
has ever made such a call and this indicates that a new situation
of intense competition in business in both the local currency and
foreign exchange will occur as Shanghai opens its financial sector
wider and the overall financial business size keeps expanding
rapidly, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Mao said that both financial service and management improved in
Shanghai in 1997 while commercial banks reported good economic
returns.
</P>
<P>
However, as the financial sector opens wider, Chinese financial
institutions must improve their foreign exchange business in
settlements, letters of credit and deposits and loans.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts must be made to improve the competitiveness of Chinese
financial institutions in foreign exchange business," Mao said.
</P>
<P>
The local branches of the Bank of China (BOC), China
Construction Bank, Industrial and Commercial Bank of China,
Agricultural Bank of China, and Bank of Communications have been
engaged in foreign-exchange business for years.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai branch of BOC, China's largest foreign exchange
bank, reported hard currency savings of 2.6 billion US dollars at
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai branches of the Everbright Bank of China, Huaxia
Bank, Fujian Industrial Bank, China Merchants Bank, and Guangdong
Development Bank have also been approved to deal in business in
foreign exchange. This year they will take measures to increase
their foreign-exchange deposits in proportion to their total value
of deposits. 
</P>
