<HEADLINE> Dhaka Recovers US$1.4 Billion of Loans in 11 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
recovered 65.57 billion taka (about 1.45 billion U.S. dollars) of
default loans from January to November last year, a local press
report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria in
the parliament Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the achievement to measures by the
government to restore discipline and efficiency in the banking
sector and realize the default loans which, local press reports
said, stood at about 100 billion taka (some 3.54 billion dollars)
at the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the percentage of outstanding loans has come down
to 35 percent from 41 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken steps against bank loan defaulters,
the minister said, assuring the parliament that further actions
would be taken to expedite the recovery rate.
</P>
<P>
A high-powered task force headed by the governor of Bangladesh
Bank, the central bank, has been set up to monitor the progress of
the task forces in commercial banks in realizing the outstanding
loans, he added.  
</P>
