<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wreckages of 2,000 Ancient Sunk Ships Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Archaeologists say they have
detected wreckages of 2,000 sunk ships dating from the Tang
(618-907) to the Qing (1644-1911) Dynasty in the coastal areas of
southern China.
</P>
<P>
Underwater archaeologists from the Beijing-based National
Museum of Chinese History have obtained pottery, coins and bronze
cannons from the wreckages which were found in eastern Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
"The wreckages indicate that there are at least 2,000 sunk
ships lying on the ancient seabed," an archaeologist said.
</P>
<P>
"And one of the sunk ships belonged to the fleet led by Admiral
Zheng Chenggong from the late Ming Dynasty (1368-1644)," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Admiral Zheng led a rebellion against the newly-established
Manchurian empire in eastern Guangdong in 1646, according to
historical sources.
</P>
<P>
Many of the ancient ship wreckages were found buried in
present-day land area such as that at the mouth of the Pearl
River, which used to be water areas.
</P>
<P>
"The findings will shed new light on the ancient maritime trade
route through the South China Sea, " said Zhang Wei, director of
underwater archaeology in the National Museum of Chinese History.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang, Chinese underwater archaeologists will make
South China Sea as their major research area in the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
China's underwater archaeology study was started in the late
1980s. By now the Chinese archaeologists have carried out a number
of underwater archaeology projects including salvaging wreckages
from a sunk ship dating back to the Liao Dynasty (916-1125) in in
northern China's Bohai Sea, archaeological investigation around
the Xisha Islands in the South China Sea and assisting Japanese
researchers in underwater archaeology study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Issue Transitional Licenses to Estate Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Estate Agents
Authority (EAA) will issue traditional licenses to estate agents
at the end of 1998, Marvin Cheung Kin-tung, chairman of the EAA
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A two-year transitional period will be allowed during which the
estate agents trade will be required to upgrade itself in order to
convert its transitional licenses into full ones before 2001,
Cheung told reporters at a press briefing Thursday afternoon after
the second meeting of the EAA.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at promoting professionalism in the trade,
enhancing protection for consumers and encouraging fair and honest
property transactions, Cheung said.
</P>
<P>
"The two-year transitional period will allow the trade
reasonable and sufficient time to meet the full licensing
requirements," he explained.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the tentative date for the issue of
transitional licenses by the end of 1998, the EAA will set
licensing requirements for the issue of transitional licenses and
full licenses, Cheung said.
</P>
<P>
The EAA will prescribe procedures in connection with
application for licenses and draw up rules and practicing
guidelines to regulate the conduct and practice of the trade, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The EAA will also discuss with educational/vocational training
institutions to facilitate the provision of training courses for
the trade and consider the need for an examination/assessment
system.
</P>
<P>
To examine these matters, the EAA has established four standing
committees, namely the Practice Committee, the Licensing
Committee, the Training Committee and the Disciplinary Committee,
Cheung said.
</P>
<P>
These committees will submit their recommendations to the EAA
in due course, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will listen to the views of the trade and the public.
Consultation and publicity will be arranged around mid-1998 on our
proposed licensing requirements and traditional arrangements,"
Cheung said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
