<HEADLINE> Joint Venture to Produce Aircraft Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Aviation Industries of
China (AIC), Boeing Company and Hexcel Corporation from the US
announced here today that they are nearing the conclusion of
negotiations to form a joint venture to manufacture composite
parts for commercial airplanes.
</P>
<P>
Financial terms of the joint venture were not disclosed today,
but a Boeing official said that the three parties will share the
investment as well as risk and profits.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will be set up in a high-tech industry zone
in north China's Tianjin municipality. It will produce fabricated
parts for secondary structural and interior applications on
commercial aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture will supply these parts to Hexcel's facility
in the US for final assembly, inspection and shipment to Boeing
and to other customers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The facility is expected to be completed in 18-24 months after
the signing of the contract and the first batch of parts will be
delivered to customers in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of this joint venture is conducive to AIC's
long-term goal of access to the world market, said an official
from the AIC.
</P>
<P>
The Hexcel also said that the cooperation will help it to
"establish a presence" in China and expand its activities in the
Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
Boeing predicts that it will sell 1,900 civil airplanes to
China in the future and will launch more cooperation projects with
the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
