<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 40,000 Ugandans Lose Limbs in War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Over 40,000 Ugandans have lost
their arms and legs due to mines in the war in the north, United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICIEF) has said.
</P>
<P>
In an 11-year guerilla war in northern districts Kitgum and
Gulu, at least 600 young girls and 1,060 young boys are in need
of care to treat their mental and physical wounds.
</P>
<P>
There are large a number of orphans and traumatized children
in the north, but no exact number of mine victims was given.
</P>
<P>
World Food Program report attributed the decrease of
casualties reports in the north to both the possible mines
cleared by the rebels of the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) and
successful consolidation of the defense in Uganda-Sudan border by
Uganda army. Uganda army stopped to use mines earlier.
</P>
<P>
Some 285,000 of 705,000 tribe residents in the region, or 40
percent of the population in the two districts, are forced to
live on food relief provided by World Food Program (WFP) in
protected camps in the region due to the attacks and harassment
from IRA rebels, WFP added.
</P>
<P>
Deficiency of vitamin A, B and iron caused widespread corneal
ulceration and childhood blindness in the protected camps, WFP
added. There has been an average of 13,000 mal-nourishment cases
among children and 6,000 vulnerable adults (pregnant/lactating
mothers, disabled and the elderly) a month since January 1997,
indications from various sources said.
</P>
<P>
About 26.4 percent of population in protected camps are
children aged at 5.14, The Monitor said today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all children are out of school since July 1996 when the
war in the region escalated, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
LRA has launched an 11-year guerilla war in northern district
of Kkitgum and Gulu against the present government led by
President Yoweri Museveni. But the number of the rebels reduced
from its usual 2,000 to hundreds recently.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has 45 districts. There were three rebel groups in the
country. The government has crushed down one of them -- the west
Nile Bank Front, the ranks of the third one -- the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF), also has shrunk from 1,500 a year ago to
hundreds now.  
</P>
</TEXT>
