<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liquor With World's Longest Cellaring Time Found in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- About four tons of cellared
liquor, with a history of more than 150 years, were recently
discovered in Jinzhou city in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Experts said it has the longest cellaring time in the world.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion has been verified by China National Food
Industry Association and Liaoning Archaeological Research
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The liquor was found on the construction site of the Lingchuan
Brewery in the city in June 1996, and was held in four huge wooden
containers. Inscriptions on the cover of the containers in both
Chinese and Manchu characters said they were sealed in the 25th
year of the Daoguang Emperor's reign of the Qing Dynasty, or
A.D. 1845. The containers also carried the mark of Tongshengjin,
an imperial workshop to produce liquor of tribute.
</P>
<P>
After one and a half century's storage, the liquor is of light
yellow and pure and mellow. The liquor, tested by a related
department, is up to the state hygiene standard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
