<HEADLINE> Two US Computer Giants Help Modernize Small Chinese Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The US's information giants,
Hewlett-Packard (HP) and Microsoft, signed a cooperation agreement
this week in Beijing to develop computer systems for four million
small and medium-sized enterprises in China.
</P>
<P>
Ricky Lee, vice president of China Hewlett-Packard Ltd., said
that small and medium-sized enterprises account for 80 percent of
the country's total, but that the use of computer technology is
limited because of technological backwardness and limited
financial muscle.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the two companies will develop a
"Small Enterprise Strategy" to increase computerization. The first
step will have HP increasing cooperation with local software
developers to provide software solutions for small and
medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The software program has gotten the support of dozens of
domestic software firms and will see to it that Chinese have more
information exchanges with the global software industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qi, director of the Ministry of Electronics Industry's
Computer and Information Technology Promotion Department, said
that 3.4 million personal computers were sold in China last year,
up 38.3 percent from the previous year, providing a good
foundation for the local software industry.
</P>
<P>
She said that small and medium-sized enterprises make up
four-fifths of the country's 5.2 million enterprises and are
expected to contribute the most to the Chinese software industry
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
