<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ox Painter Hopes to Draw Spanish Ox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- It is perhaps the right time
for a Chinese well versed in drawing ox to have the idea of going
to Spain to draw a foreign ox.
</P>
<P>
1997-98 was the year of ox according to Chinese lunar calendar
and a great year for professional artist Ding Luo, 60, a farmer's
son who have drawn 100,000 oxen.
</P>
<P>
But he had not seen a foreign ox until he was 50.
</P>
<P>
"I first saw a foreign ox on TV ten years ago. It was the bull
fighting in Spain. I was stunned to find that the foreign ox is a
strange animal and it is different from its Chinese relatives," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On Ding's mind for years, a Chinese ox is honest, hard working
and always quiet and timid. However, the Spanish bull he saw on
TV, is untamed and always fight to win.
</P>
<P>
What the artist referred to is perhaps a "cultural ox", people
guess. All they know is that at that moment, Ding did not come
across the idea of drawing a Spanish ox.
</P>
<P>
But last year made him think in a different way. The reclusive
Ding was invited to step out his house in Beijing's suburbs and
draw oxen for different people, who all think the ox is an
auspicious animal, and thus the artist got the chance to visit
many parts of China.
</P>
<P>
What a great change had the folk artist seen! In Shenzhen, he
was moved by the enthusiastic celebrations for the return of Hong
Kong, and in Shanghai, he was astonished with the skyscrapers in
the economic development areas.
</P>
<P>
"Suddenly, I realized the world has grown larger in the past
years, and smaller as well, and shouldn't I go to the outside
world to have a look in rest of my life?" the farmer's son
proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the Board of the Directors of the Chinese
Contemporary Painting and Calligraphy, Ding's works were published
on the elite "People's Daily", and were on display abroad. But he
did not go to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Ding is a master of traditional Chinese painting, and he
thought that the technique could be only used to depict
traditional Chinese landscape and rural life. No foreign things
are accepted.
</P>
<P>
"But now I think that it is not a bad idea to let Westerners
have a look of our Chinese ox, and bring the image of the Western
ox back to my country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his first destination will surely be Spain, as
the bull fighting on TV has impressed him most.
</P>
<P>
It's the 5,000-year-old agricultural civilization that has
cultivated China, and ox was an important element for such a
culture. The ox, who always unselfishly contribute to the people,
was praised by intellectuals as a moral example.
</P>
<P>
Ding said that the ox's vantages are gradually disappearing as
modern economy and science develop so fast, and changes should
thus be made in painting styles as well.
</P>
<P>
"Thus I have been trying to depict the ox's another aspect: the
spirit of bold exploration, which is an unusual theme for
traditional Chinese painting," he said.
</P>
<P>
The result is that some of his animals no longer keep silent,
but rush ahead like horses, shouting loudly.
</P>
<P>
The rebelling artist is now making preparations for his Spanish
journey by studying the habits of Western oxen as well as climate
and culture in that distant country.
</P>
<P>
"To draw oxen abroad? It is difficult," said Zhou Ben, a
newspaper editor and a friend of Ding. "He even does not know how
expensive the travel will be."
</P>
<P>
"But I was still moved by his novel idea," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Taking Measures to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The government and the
tourist circles of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) are taking measures to attract more visitors and maintain
Hong Kong as a dynamic and powerful tourist magnet.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon held by the Hong Kong General Chamber of
 Commerce, Executive Director of the Hong Kong Tourist Association
 (HKTA) Amy Chan said Hong Kong's tourism industry is facing a
difficult year, after a decade of spectacular growth, due to a
regional economic downturn sweeping East Asia over the last few
months.
</P>
<P>
She highlighted some of the measures and initiatives currently
being undertaken in Hong Kong as the following:
</P>
<P>
-- The SAR is considering a series of actions including
shortening the visa application process for Taiwan citizens and
processing direct visa applications from Russia, Eastern Europe
and the Middle East;
</P>
<P>
-- The HKTA has received a pledge of a 100 million HK dollar
(12.85 million U.S. dollars) loan from the SAR government to
support its "Spotlight Hong Kong" program, which will help
consolidate Hong Kong's position as Asia's "leading events
capital."
</P>
<P>
-- The HKTA has recommended to the SAR government tax-cutting
measures to help the industry, including reduction in the Airport
Departure Tax or Hotel and Accommodation Tax, and it has also
asked the SAR government to alleviate the financial burden on the
hotel and catering industry by waiving the Trade Effluent
Surcharge.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, along with East Asia, is facing a difficult year,
but it is still Asia's number one tourist destination, Chan
said. Even in last year's downturn, Hong Kong received about 10.4
million visitors -- at least 25 percent more than anywhere else in
 the region.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that our vision for Hong Kong as the region's
premier visitor destination is the right one and achievable," Chan
concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Getting Rid of Poverty in Eastern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The final two million poor
people in China's Jiangsu province have been brought out of
poverty as the province met its state-set poverty-eradication
goals three years ago.
</P>
<P>
China began the ambitious program in 1994 to help 80 million
poor people get out of poverty by the end of the century. China
now has 58 million poor people.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income in ten of Jiangsu's poorest counties is now
2,516 yuan, well above the provincial poverty line of 800
yuan. The poverty line for the country as a whole is 500
yuan. But, Jiangsu developed an economic gap between its northern
and southern parts. So, in 1994, it began calling for cooperative
efforts to help the poor northern part get out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
For the past three years, southern counties have helped their
poorer counterparts with 300 profitable projects, and the province
completed several projects to help improve living and working
conditions in the region, building roads for every township,
bringing electricity to nearly all villages, transforming
low-yield farmland, and in water conservation.
</P>
<P>
The efforts have paid off. In 1997, the poor region's GDP was
29.1 billion yuan, up 15.7 percent from the previous year, and
grain output was 18.75 billion kilograms, accounting for 51
percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
The province will continue its preferential policies for the
region for the next three years, the provincial government says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
