<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Serious Ice Jams Unlikely in Lower Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 22 (Xinhua) -- As of yesterday, ice covered a
323-km stretch of the Yellow River, China's second longest river,
but experts say it's unlikely that serious ice jams will affect
the lower reaches this spring.
</P>
<P>
A coldfront has affected Shandong Province in eastern China
since January 15, bringing with it a long cold spell. The five
million cu.m. of ice on this section of the Yellow River is five
to 12 cm thick.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, although the amount of ice and water
levels are the highest they've been for the past three years, the
amount of discharge is still lower than normal, and catastrophic
floods do not seem likely when it thaws.
</P>
<P>
The Shandong section of the Yellow River has had several
disastrous ice jams and bank breaches in history because of the
great drop in elevation from the upper reaches on the Loess
Plateau, to the lower.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Japanese Man's Half-Century China Odyssey  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- For Ryutaro Hasegawa, the
senior advisor of the Japan Association for the Promotion of
International Trade (JAPIT), the 53-year post-World-War-II period
has been a "China-centered journey".
</P>
<P>
The 90-year-old man became interested in China when he first
visited the country at the age of 12, and has visited it 77 times
since then.
</P>
<P>
One day, when he was riding a train across the vast expanse of
endless fields at dusk, he saw the setting sun turn a picturesque
crimson color, and it was then that he fell in love with the great
country.
</P>
<P>
After graduating from college, he decided that he wanted to do
something in China, and this dream eventually drove him to be a
pioneer in Sino-Japanese economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In 1957, Hasegawa came to do business in China as an employee
of one of Mitsubishi's companies and he attended the import and
export fair in Guangzhou, which became a window for China's
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
In trying to solve China's nitrogenous fertilizer shortage
problem in the 1950s, Hasegawa went from place to place in search
of 700,000 tons of fertilizer and shipped it to China.
</P>
<P>
The JAPIT was founded in 1954, and Hasegawa helped its
oil-import branch to get oil from China's Daqing Oilfield, which
was opened in the early 1960s. Since the 1950s, his company has
gotten aluminum and manganese from China's Bohai Bay, and he has
shipped textile and chemical equipment to China.
</P>
<P>
Many difficulties in Sino-Japanese economic and trade relations
in the 1950s because the diplomatic relations between China and
Japan had yet to be normalized. Goods then were trans-shipped
through Hong Kong, Thailand, or other places. Hasegawa said,
however, that he neither regretted nor felt proud of what he did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Ancient Town Well Preserved in Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Pingyao, an ancient town in
northwest China's Shanxi Province, which has been listed as one of
World Cultural Heritage sites last year, will be developed into a
tourism, commercial and film town with distinctive features, said
a local official.
</P>
<P>
Cao Changzhi, vice-director of the provincial construction
committee, said that related governments have worked out a series
of plans to rationally develop the town on the basis of
comprehensive conservation.
</P>
<P>
Cao said the plans will be carried out within three years, and
will focus on the renovation of the ancient Mingqing Street,
hundred years old stores and government offices, ancient temples
and city walls, as well as dwelling houses of local style.
</P>
<P>
In addition, local governments will invest more than 210
million yuan (about 25.3 million US dollars) to move large
enterprises out of the ancient town area, purchase about 30
typical local-style houses from local residents, and build some
cultural relics museums in the first decade of next century,
according to Cao.
</P>
<P>
Cao emphasized that the tourism development of the town should
be coordinated with the protection of the cultural relics, and the
uniqueness of the town should be kept intact.
</P>
<P>
The town is home to more than 40,000 population, over one
hundred enterprises, as well as nearly 4,000 traditional
residences and ancient shops, most of which are still in use. And
the town is facing growing population pressure and backward
infrastructure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
