<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Arms Producers Complain Budget Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Armscor, South Africa's
arms manufacturer, has warned there was a real danger that most
armament manufacturing companies in the country would not survive
the current reductions in the defense budget.
</P>
<P>
Local daily the Citizen quoted unidentified sources as
reporting today that no arms producer has received major arms
contracts from the South African National Defense Forces (SANDF)
this year, and there was little hope of new contracts being
awarded unless the defense budget was increased.
</P>
<P>
Some arms companies have tried to switch from weapons
manufacturing to commercial products. However, this strategy was
not successful in all cases and thousands of workers have been
paid off, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, South African arms giant Denel company said
its head office personnel would be cut by between 40 and 50
percent before the end of February, and that its board members
would be reduced by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Denel Managing Director Seshi Chonco said that the board would
be reduced to seven members from the current 14, and that about
half of its 190 employees would be retrenched.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the drastic reduction in the defense budget and the
resulting reduction in military order for new weapons.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified Armscore source said the capital budget for
the SANDF had been reduced to such an extent in the past five
years that the SANDF could barely afford to maintain weapons
systems and had no money left to buy new weapons.
</P>
<P>
He said although South Africa had been on the edge of
technology in areas such as artillery and aircraft avionics, no
research and development had been done for the past year.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, in a very short time the SANDF will be forced to
buy all new weapons systems abroad because without research and
development South African armaments companies will not be able to
supply the SANDF with technically competitive weapons," the
sources added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
