<HEADLINE> Sea Gulls Returning to Chaohu Lake in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- "The birds are so lovely," said
Zhang Youshan, an elder fisherman, looking at thousands of sea
gulls at Chaohu Lake, one of the country's five largest freshwater
lakes.
</P>
<P>
"This contributes to the efforts made by local government last
December to persuade fishermen living around the lake in east
China's Anhui Province to move their densely set fishing nets away
from the water," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The 87-square-km lake in Anhui Province used to be rich in
fish resources, which attracted flocks of sea gulls wintering here
before the 1980s. The birds seldom flew to the lake in recent
winters because they couldn't find food because of over-fishing.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and other fishermen have removed more than 10,000 fishing
nets from the lake, which has again become an attractive wintering
place for sea gulls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Japanese Man's Half-Century China Odyssey (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He recalled having visited in the early 1960s the Daqing
Oilfield in northeast China where living conditions were so poor
that he could hardly believe his eyes -- the shoddy equipment and
cotton clothing patched with rags. He did feel that the Chinese
were extraordinary people and that the country would recover in
the future.
</P>
<P>
In the ensuing years, he saw China's economy greatly improve in
about 20 years and then make a giant leap in a decade, and finally
reach a new level in just five years' time, he explained.
</P>
<P>
In his old age, he still works hard for economic and trade
ties, and joins the JAPIT delegation's China visit every year. His
Sasebo Heavy Industries Co., Ltd. is working in cooperation with
the China Ocean Shipping Corporation in the shipbuilding industry.
</P>
<P>
His company is planning on setting up a thermo-electric power
company in Harbin, the capital of China's northermost Heilongjiang
Province and one purpose of his current visit, as a member of
JAPIT's 26th delegation, is aimed to have a look at the
preparatory work.
</P>
<P>
Hasegawa said that both the Japanese and Chinese economies have
undergone great changes in the past several decades but that the
two have grown close than ever before, and that the two countries
should treat each other openly, capitalize each other's
advantages, and join hands to create a still better future.
</P>
</TEXT>
