<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Investments Flow to South Korea in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investments in South
Korea hit 5.93 billion U.S. dollars in the first 11 months in
1997, up about 155 percent from the same period of 1996, the
Ministry of Finance and Economy said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in the form of purchases of equities, which
was officially allowed by the government last February, totaled
601 million dollars during the same period, accounting for just 10
percent of the total foreign investment volume, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign investments in the country fell to 91 million
dollars last November, 62.1 percent down from the same month of
1996, due to the financial crisis caused by the collapse of large
conglomerates and bad loans of financial institutions late 1997,
said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The sharp reductions in foreign investments, compared with 361
million dollars for October, reflected plunging overseas
investors' confidence in the country's financial market after the
International Monetary Fund agreed to provide the nation with the
rescue loans of 57 billion dollars tied with stiff conditions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Korea's overseas investments tumbled 49.8
percent to 248 million dollars last November from the same month
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the first 11 months in 1997, the nation's investments
overseas was 5.09 billion dollars, down 1.5 percent from the same
time of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the drop of overseas investments by
South Korean firms to the economic slowdown triggered by the
bankruptcy of large conglomerates and then a liquidity crunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
