<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Laid-off Workers Working in Neighborhood Committees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,800 laid-off
workers in Beijing have found their new positions in neighborhood
committees, said Zhang Guixing, an official from Beijing Civil
Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Neighborhood Committees, used to be made up by housewives and
the elders, play an unique role in maintaining public order in
China. However, the elders and women can not cope with some
accidents such as catching thieves.
</P>
<P>
With the number of the laid-off workers increasing in recent
years, many of them have found jobs in the neighhood committees.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing has about 5,430 neighborhood committees, employing
more than 22,000 people, with the laid-off workers being the new
blood," said Zhang, adding that, "The new members are younger and
better educated."
</P>
<P>
Niu Jinying, a member of a neighborhood committee in Xisi in
downtown Beijing, said that she lost her job in 1993, and then
found the new job in the neighborhood committee.
</P>
<P>
"The committee has become my new home. I do some cleaning in
the residential quarters in the daytime, and then call on the
families with difficulties. If any family is at quarrels, I'll go
to mediate," said Niu.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-one-year-old Li Wenhui of a neighborhood committee in
western Beijing said that, "We old men can feel relieved after
younger men joined our committee."
</P>
<P>
Wang Shuzhen, 42, said, "After I became the chief of a
neighborhood committee I have changed a lot. Working with the
elders, I feel I'm still very young and full of vigor."
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics of the Municipal Labor Bureau, more
than 137,000 laid-off workers in Beijing were re-employed in
1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
