<HEADLINE> More Textile Workers Cut Down in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the economic center
of China, cut its employees in the textile sector by 270,000 last
year, the Economic Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Shanghai's 1997 textile output value
was roughly the same as that of 1996, while the industry payroll
dropped from 550,000 to 280,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's textile sector achieved its projected profit of 300
million yuan last year, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, the textile sector accounted for 10 percent of the
losses suffered by all of China's state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
This year China will scrap 4.8 million spindles and reduce its
number of textile workers by 600,000. 
</P>
