<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks in Zambia Swindled Out of 790,000 Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Commercial banks in Zambia were
swindled out of 1.1 billion Kwacha (about 790,000 U.S. Dollars)
in 1997, Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Chief Security Commandant of Bank
of Zambia, Nober Mumba, as saying here Wednesday that the 1.1
billion Kwacha represented a fraction of what was stolen from the
banking sector because several commercial banks did not report
cases of fraud to the Central Bank fearing they would shatter
their reputation.
</P>
<P>
He told the Zambia police conference on crime that the
organized crime is threatening economic recovery and should be
tackled seriously by all interest groups.
</P>
<P>
Money channelled to Zambia's neighboring countries through
fraud could not be retrieved because of lack of treaties to deal
with such cases, according to the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion Inspector General of Police Francis
Ndhlovu said between January and July last year 37 vehicles
stolen from the neighboring countries were recovered in Zambia
while 15 vehicles stolen from Zambia were found in the
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 and 1997 a total of 4,600 counterfeit video and audio
tapes were confiscated in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of policemen will be increased to 27,000 by
the year 2000 from current 12,000.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa told the meeting that
violent crime is a danger to democracy while organized crime
does a lot of damage to the economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister said crime impedes economic growth and
discourages investors and it should be tackled vigorously.
</P>
</TEXT>
