<HEADLINE> Technology of Rapid Propagation of Bamboo Developed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A new technology of rapid
propagation of bamboo has helped increase the growing areas of
bamboo in southwestern China's Yunnan Province to 16,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The province is referred as the hometown of bamboo, which is
widely used in local people's daily life. And in recent years, the
demand for bamboo has increased sharply because of the wide use of
it in industrial production. Statistics showed that more than
3,000 bamboo products falling into seven categories have been
developed in China.
</P>
<P>
However, traditional method of planting bamboo can not meet the
rapidly increasing demand. By the current method, the surviving
rate of bamboo can only reach 20 to 50 percent, and it takes five
to six years to build a forest of bamboo.
</P>
<P>
A paper plant in Shuangjiang County in the province consumes
40,000 tons of bamboo annually, and the bamboo in the county can
only sustain the production of the plant for no more than three
years.
</P>
<P>
The Bamboo Research Institute of Yunnan Teacher's College has
developed the new technology of rapid propagation of bamboo.
</P>
<P>
They treated a branch of bamboo with a special liquid, and then
plant the branch. After five monthes, the branch will grow to 2.5
meters high. By this method, 30 to 50 young plants can grow out of
an adult bamboo.
</P>
<P>
The surviving rate of the new method can reach 90 percent, and
the time of building a bamboo forest will be reduced within two
years. Researches have showed that the new technology can be
applied to more than a dozen species of bamboo.
</P>
<P>
The research institute has trained more than 16,000 local
farmers to spread the new method to over 20 counties.
</P>
<P>
An expert of the institute said that they will continue their
research to improve the planting method.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
