<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Water to Flow to S. Africa Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A huge dam and tunnel
project will send water from Lesotho mountains to South Africa's
parched north today after 11 years of construction at a cost of
10 billion Rand (2.03 billion U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela and Lesotho King Letsie
III will preside over a colorful dedication ceremony in northern
mountains of the small kingdom surrounded by South Africa, the
Citizen paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho Highlands Water Project will reverse the southerly
flow of water out of Lesotho's mountains, sending it 400
kilometers north to Gauteng, South Africa's industrial heartland,
and other regions.
</P>
<P>
Work on the project started in 1986 after the signing of a
treaty between South Africa's previous government and Lesotho,
which was aimed to solve water shortage in northern South Africa
while generating big revenues for Lesotho, one of the world's 10
poorest nations listed by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
By selling its principal natural resource, Lesotho gets
millions of Rand in fees from South African water consumers and a
72-megawatt hydro-electric plant, enough to supply all its power
needs.
</P>
<P>
The scheme enables South Africa's north and northeast regions
to receive additional water for about 30 years, which is expected
to quench the growing thirst in major industrial neighborhood and
bring about an economic boom in some less developed areas,
including eastern Free State towns.
</P>
<P>
Capturing water from snow in the mountains 2,000 meters above
the sea, the project combines one of Africa's tallest dams, at
184 meters, with an 80 kilometers tunnel under the Maluti
Mountains. More than 200 kilometers of roads and a bridge over
the Malibamatso River were built to transport construction
material to the dam site.
</P>
<P>
South African Water Affairs Minister Kader Asmal has hailed
the project as a role model in regional cooperation, providing
"an integrated unified approach" to develop the two countries
whose "economic destinies are inextricably linked". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
