<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan Takes Lead in Offering Jobs to the Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- More than half of the disabled
persons in south China's island province of Hainan have been
employed, thanks to the efforts of local governments.
</P>
<P>
The number of the disabled persons in the province stands at
300,000, making up 4.3 percent of the total population. 66,000 out
of 106,000 disabled persons who reach the age of working have
found jobs.
</P>
<P>
The central government has stipulated that local governments
should provide employment opportunities for disabled persons. And
Hainan provincial government requires that the disabled persons
should account for 1.5 percent of the total employees in the
government organs, institutes and enterprises. If the enterprises
and government organs can not employ as many handicapped persons
as required, they have to pay pensions for the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
Many employment service centers for the disabled have been set
up across the province, providing information, pre-post training,
consultation and various services.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the province will try to increase the employment
rate of the disabled to 80 percent by the end of the year 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
