<HEADLINE> Mandela Eases His Working Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHANNESBURG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- With his takeover as head
of state in 1999 just around the corner, deputy president Thabo
Mbeki is set to move to the center stage and assume most of the
functions currently performed by president Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
President spokesman Parks Mankahlana said yesterday with the
hand-over reins to Mbeki so close, Mandela's schedule would be
rearranged to make the transition "smooth and comfortable".
</P>
<P>
"The president will definitely tone down his schedule to give
Mbeki responsibility," Mankahlana was quoted as saying by local
press today.
</P>
<P>
In several instances last year Mandela said he regarded
himself as the de jure president and Mbeki the de factor head of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, Mankahlana could not confirm whether Mandela would
spend much of his spare time at his favority retreat in Qunu, his
home village in Eastern Cape province.
</P>
<P>
Recently at the African National Congress (ANC) national
conference, the 79 year old president stepped down as leader of
the ruling party, handing over to Mbeki, a move seen by many as
preparing for Mbeki's eventual takeover as the country's next
president. 
</P>
