<HEADLINE> Tianjin to Strengthen Operations of State-owned Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, a leading industrial
center in north China, has introduced measures to extricate
medium- to large-sized state-owned enterprises from difficult
positions within the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The number of loss-making firms will account for 20 percent,
with the volume of loss expected to fall by 10 percent in the
period. In addition, their assets to liabilities ratio will be
reduced to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to achieve the target by reorganizing
state-owned enterprises, and establishing a number of
trans-regional, trans-trade and multiple ownership enterprise
groups, as well as promoting enterprise mergers and joint stock
corporations.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 loss-making enterprises will be forced into bankruptcy
or be merged over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The city will also upgrade existing technology and equipment in
order to develop new value-added products with high market
potential.  
</P>
</TEXT>
