<HEADLINE> Guangdong Provincial Increases Trade Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
province recorded a total 1997 import-export value of 130.12
billion U.S. dollars, up 18.3 percent on the previous year,
according to China's International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
Exports rose by 25.6 percent to 74.56 billion US dollars, with
imports hitting 55.56 billion US dollars, up 9.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province used foreign funding of 14.2
billion US dollars in 1997, up 2.2 percent from the year before.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of ordinary exports to the total exports
outstripped that of foreign-funded enterprises, with 21
provincial cities reported varying increases. The province has
moved forward in expanding its international market and the
processing trade sector has witnessed continuing growth, according
to the Daily.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises from over 70 countries or regions have invested in
Guangdong, with increased rationalization in the flow of funds. In
addition, the province has restructured the composition of export
products, with an increase of the volume of high-tech products.
</P>
<P>
Exports of computers and accessories hit eight billion US
dollars and accounted for close to 10 percent of Guangdong's total
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
