<HEADLINE> More Educational Exchanges Between Inland Areas, Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Educational exchanges between
inland areas and Hong Kong are expanding into broader fields with
an increasing number of programs added since the return of Hong
Kong to the motherland in July.
</P>
<P>
Li Haiji, director of the Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan Affairs
Office of the State Education Commission (SEC), told Xinhua in a
recent interview that educational exchanges between inland areas
and Hong Kong are mainly in the form of seminars, mutual visits
and educating postgraduates.
</P>
<P>
His office invited more than 1,500 students and teachers from
Hong Kong last year, and sent 3,100 people to Hong Kong for
academic exchanges, he said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have benefited by improving educational levels and
accelerating reforms through the increase of mutual understanding
in the exchanges, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said Hong Kong has abundant information resource and has
access to transforming scientific knowledge into production, while
institutions of higher learning in inland areas have many
talents. He added that it is an important job to study how to
combine advantages of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He pledged the SEC will continue to support the two-way
educational exchanges, and try to conduct more and long-term
cooperative projects.
</P>
<P>
He said the SEC welcomes Hong Kong primary and middle school
students to inland areas, and plans to organize at least 50
visiting groups this year to increase their understanding of the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The SEC will enhance links with teachers and presidents of
schools in Hong Kong, and cooperation among colleges on both sides
will be further developed, he said.
</P>
<P>
By request of Hong Kong colleges, educational departments in
inland areas will send some students in inland areas to study in
Hong Kong, while inland areas will continue to recruit Hong Kong
students, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
