<HEADLINE> Guangdong's Open-up Not Affected by Southeast Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis in
Southeast Asia will not affect the open-up of the financial sector
in Guangdong, said Xiao Gang, director of Guangdong Branch of the
People's Bank of China, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
He told a provincial financial work conference which opened
yesterday that Guangdong's financial sector has been running
soundly and the open-up of the sector has never been slowed down
in the past years.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, we may step up the open-up in accordance with
practical conditions in future," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The newly-appointed director noted that by the end of 1997,
the presence of overseas financial institutions in Guangdong
(Shenzhen not included) reached 68, of which 25 are
profit-making. Last year, four more overseas financial institutions
were approved to set up offices in the province.
</P>
<P>
The business volume of these overseas banks and financial
institutions has hit 3.6 billion US dollars, accounting for one
tenth of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
In the move to open up, five financial institutions of
Guangdong have opened business overseas.
</P>
<P>
Xiao said the province plans to guide overseas financial
institutions to expand business in eastern and western areas of
the province as well as the mountainous areas in the north.
</P>
<P>
The province also pledges to enhance study and information
exchanges with the overseas financial sector.  
</P>
