<HEADLINE> Northern Chinese Province Expands Highway Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Three expressways opened
to traffic in north China's Hebei Province in 1997, bringing the
total length of expressways in Hebei to 575 kilometers, a
provincial official said recently.
</P>
<P>
The Hebei section of the first phase of the Tangshan-Tianjin
Expressway began operation Nov. 28. Work on the six-lane road
started in August of 1995. It is 47 kilometers long and cost 1.2
billion yuan. Its second phase should be completed in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The expressway linking Tangshan with the Jing-Tang-Gang
expressway started operation on Dec. 6. Construction of the
81.2-kilometer-long road started in May, 1996 with an investment
of 1.65 billion yuan raised by governments of Hebei and
Tangshan. Its going into service is expected to speed up economic
growth in the Beijing-Tianjin-Hebei economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The 216-kilometer-long expressway between Shijiazhuang, capital
of Hebei, and Anyang in Henan Province, opened Dec. 30. It cost
4.6 billion yuan, including 240 million U.S. dollars in loans
offered by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
