<HEADLINE> Fujian Develops Hi-tech Electronics Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Baiyi Electronic Information
Center in Fuzhou, capital of east China's Fujian Province, has
signed 10 hi-tech contracts with investors from the United States,
Japan, and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
An official with the center, dubbed Silicon Valley of Fujian,
said that the contracts carry a total a value of 120 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The two major contracts -- a Sino-U.S. joint venture to
produce personal computers and Taiwan-funded enterprise --
involve total investments of some 30 million U.S. dollars each,"
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The center, which plans to attract more investors, has built a
number of infrastructure facilities, including a water plant,
transformer substation, roads, a gas pipeline, plant workshops and
an apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
The center, which covers three sq.km., is the largest
electronics production base in Fujian. The province has approved
94 electronics enterprises and joint-ventures for the center, with
a total investments approaching 800 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Said enterprises recorded a 1997 industrial production value of
four billion yuan, a 1.1-fold rise on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The center will extend great efforts to realize its goal of
reaching a production value of 20 billion yuan by 2000, a figure
which will account for 33 percent of the provincial total. 
</P>
