<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's state bank seeks idle dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A strong demand for foreign
currency has prompted Vietnam's State Bank to request enterprises
to sell idle U.S. dollars in their hands for the Vietnamese dong,
the "Vietnam News" reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily quoted State Bank officials as
saying that the foreign currency market in Vietnam is "unbalanced"
with some enterprises hoarding dollars while others suffer from a
shortage.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is being compounded by the poor management at many
banks which tend to leave capital idle rather than rechannelling
it back into the economy," the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, many commercial banks are failing to meet the
demand for foreign currency from import-export enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Lack of foreign currency has forced many import-export
enterprises to borrow from foreign banks at a higher interest rate.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to free up the flow of foreign exchange, the
acting governor of the State Bank has told state-sector banks to
cooperate with commercial banks in encouraging all enterprises to
sell their idle dollars.
</P>
<P>
The State Bank said that the enterprises, which have sold their
dollars, will be allowed to "spot" buy and sell foreign currencies at
commercial banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
