<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Increase Confidence in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Economic reforms in
Tanzania has built up foreign businessmen's confidence in the
country, making it one of the top 10 Foreign Direct Investment
(FDI) destination in Africa.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Bank of Tanzania told the Express paper
that before liberalization of the economy few investors cared
about Tanzania. Records show that not a penny was invested in
1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
The official, who is from the Department of Economic Reform
and Policy Research of the bank, noted the country experienced a
sharp decline in the FDI following a debt crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, as the country began to make achievements in economic
reforms in recent years, the country has seen an upsurge of
investment. A report of the bank shows that between 1991 and
1996, private foreign capital to Tanzania totalled 425 million US
Dollars, twice the total amount of the years before 1995, the
weekly newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The present inflow of FDI at present is 16 times the figure in
1992. It was at pains to attract the 12 million US Dollars then,
but in 1996 the country absorbed as much as 193 million US
dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"More is expected to come following betterment of the
country's investment regime and take-off of the Dar es Salaam
Stock Exchange," the paper quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
With more influx of foreign investment, Tanzania is expected
to have more channels to the international market, opportunities of
technology transfer and business management know-how which the
east African country has yearned for.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Tanzania ranks in the seventh position in FDI
receipts to the availabilitys of untapped resources: minerals,
wildlife and arable land, all in the name of a stable political
climate.
</P>
<P>
The superb FDI record, however, has failed to please United
Nations Conference on Trade and Investment. It says although the
investment performance of Tanzania and other African countries is
improving, there is nothing to boast of.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out it is true foreign investors' interest in
Africa has grown in recent years, but the continent's share of
global investment remains low.
</P>
<P>
Inflows in 1996 amounted to 5.28 billion US Dollars. In global
terms, it was a mere 1.5 percent of the total. It was
nevertheless almost double the annual average of the late 1980s,
but below the 1994 zenith of 5.8 billion US Dollars. The share of
the developing world FDI fell to four percent from 11.2 percent
in the second half of the 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
