<HEADLINE> China Orders Seven Boeing Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese airlines ordered seven
Boeing passenger aircraft in January this year, according to
sources from related departments.
</P>
<P>
Air China signed a contract for five Boeing 737-800 passenger
aircraft on Wednesday, with Shandong Airlines ordering two 737-300
planes through the China Aviation Supply Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The purchases were part of the framework agreement Chinese
President Jiang Zemin signed during his October 1997 visit to the
United States. The agreement calls for China to purchase Boeing
passenger planes.
</P>
<P>
The most recent order represents the first time Chinese
airlines have purchased 737-800 aircraft, the newest model in the
Boeing 737 series. The new twin engine features eight first class
and 159 business class seats. The aircraft will be delivered
between August 1998 and March 2000.
</P>
<P>
The two Boeing aircraft ordered by Shandong Airlines will be
delivered between July and September this year. 
