<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Lower Economic Growth Target in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Affected by the Asian
economic crisis and terror attacks last year, Israel's economy is
expected to grow no more than 3 percent in 1998, local The
Jerusalem Post newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report by the Finance Ministry's Economic
Research and State Revenue Administration as saying that, Israel
needs to revise it original economic forecasts issued last July
before the terror attacks in Jerusalem and the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mainly affected by the July 30 bombing of Mahane Yehuda Market
and the September 4 bombing of Ben Yahuda pedestrian mall in
Jerusalem that killed about 30 people, the tourism industry
suffered badly as the number of tourists coming to Israel declined
by 3 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry predicted in its July forecast a 3-3.5
percent growth in the gross domestic product in 1998. But Tsipi
Galyam, head of the Economic Research and State Revenue
Administration, said the Asian crisis alone could reduce Israeli
economic growth by 0.2 to 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Galyam added that the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund have lowered the growth forecast of most of the
world's economies by 0.2 to 0.7 percent, so the Israeli economy
was hardly likely to emerge unscathed from this crisis. He noted
that even there would be no direct effect on Israel, the
anticipated lower growth in other countries would indirectly
affect Israeli economy.
</P>
<P>
Israeli economy has slowed down since the hardline Likud
government, which came to power in mid-1996, adopted austerity
policies aimed to reduce the huge budgetary deficit and curb high
inflation. The economic growth, averaged above 6 percent annually
before 1996, dropped to 4.2 percent in 1996 and 2.1 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Finance Ministry is drafting a comprehensive
package of macro-economic measures aimed at further reducing
inflation, cutting unemployment, and increasing growth. While the
inflation rate was cut to about 7 percent in 1997, the
unemployment rate rose to over 8 percent, causing widespread
labor unrest and social tensions.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's proposed measures will require the cooperation
of several economic bodies, including the Bank of Israel, which
will be asked to include an interest rate cut. The ministry is
prepared to maintain the inflation target in the new year the same
as 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the coming days, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
will hold consultations with Finance Minister Yaacov Neeman and
Governor of Bank of Israel Jacob Frenkel to discuss the economic
measures, including how to deal with the spiraling unemployment
and economic crisis in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans Urged to Get Rid of Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Anti-Corruption
Authority (KACA) is committed to ridding the country of
corruption; thus it urges political parties and the media to help
in the fight against corruption.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the local newspaper of Kenya times
published here today, KACA Chairman John Mwau said that his
outfit would work zealously to help repair Kenya's dented image
as a habitat for corruption.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his determination to get rid of corruption,
saying that the "mop-up operation" would not be slowed down by
the so-called "untouchables".
</P>
<P>
Mwau said that the law would apply to all irrespective of
status and challenged political parties and politicians with
evidence which can prove cases of corruption to provide it to the
authority.
</P>
<P>
He also challenged the media to help in the fight against
corruption, saying that "pen judgements and wholesome
condemnations against the authority would not suffice, we need
evidence to enable us to pursue the culprits and prosecute."
</P>
<P>
The KACA chairman noted that the corrupt practices were
currently strangling the growth of the country's economy, adding
that "this is a cancer which we must all fight."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the press would play a major role by
highlighting corrupt practices positively instead of judging the
authority with their pen.
</P>
<P>
Mwau stressed that it was President Daniel arap Moi's concern
that ills like corruption were eradicated in the country so that
Kenya becomes a better state to live in.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chairman of the kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) Peter
Nyakiamo issued a statement Tuesday, saying that KRA
Commissioner-General Yusuf Nzibo had been replaced by John
Msafari.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae
had also reinstated Samuel Chebii as the Commissioner of Customs
and Excise.
</P>
<P>
Chebii was known to have been very firm on tax evasion and his
transfer last year was precipitated by his refusal to endorse
documents to regularize sugar imported under dubious
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund halted a Key aid package for
Kenya and cited Chebii's removal as among the main factors in
discontinuing aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
