<HEADLINE> China's Tertiary Industry to Do More for Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The tertiary industry will
contribute more to China's economic development over the next
decade, according to today's Economic Daily.
</P>
<P>
Added-value output in distribution, service, and culture is
expected to account for a third of the country's GDP by 2000, the
State Planning Commission predicts. And that figure will increase
to 40 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
From 1997 to 2000, the tertiary industry will have a 9 percent
growth rate, the commission says, and the industry's market share
will increase 400 billion yuan each year. It will add 40 million
more employees between 1997 and 2000, it says.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to developing parts of the tertiary
industry with great market potential and capacity to employ
people, like tourism, housing construction, and community
services. 
</P>
