<HEADLINE> Chinese Study For Sino-American Marine Optical Cable Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A feasibility study for a
Sino-American marine optical cable in the sea area around Chinese
sea was completed recently, according to Ye Yincan of the China
National Oceanography Bureau's No.2 Institute, the engineer who
was in charge of the study.
</P>
<P>
Ye told reporters that his 40-member team, which included four
foreigners, worked from October 11, 1997 to January 6 of this
year, over a 6,500 km course.
</P>
<P>
They used four ships to study the geology and seismic activity
off the Chinese coast and on land in Zhejiang Province's Chongming
and Guangdong Province's Shantou.
</P>
<P>
The cable is scheduled for completion in 1999, and will be
financed by China, the United States, Japan, the Republic of Korea
and Australia at a cost of 1.2 billion U.S. dollars. Its total
length will be 26,500 km. It will be able to transmit four million
dialing signals, or audio, video and digital information
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Ye says that they are now analyzing samples they have collected
and will soon complete the report on their findings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
