<HEADLINE> Nigeria Arrests 60 More Coup Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian authorities have
arrested 60 more military officers as well as civilians for their
possible roles in the coup attempt last December.
</P>
<P>
Acting defense spokesman Colonel Godwin Ugbo told newsmen in
Lagos Wednesday that the suspects are now being interrogated by
the 15-man special investigation panel set up to probe into the
alleged coup plot on December 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new figure excludes 12 senior military generals arrested
earlier. Among them are Chief of General Staff, Lt.-General
Oladipo Diya, the deputy of the head of state, and two former
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Ugbo refused to identify those new arrests, saying that they
might be found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the investigation is progressing very well and
that the panel will submit its report to the government by the
end of this month as expected.
</P>
<P>
All the suspects will be tried in a military court, the
Nigerian government has said. 
