<HEADLINE> APEC Urged to Respond to Members' Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia International
Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz on Thursday urged the
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum to respond to the
economic problems of its members due to the currency turmoil in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
APEC needs to face the challenge of ensuring that its programs
remain relevant and useful in helping members overcome their
economic problems, Rafidah said at a ceremony where she announced
that the third APEC International Trade Fair '98 would be held in
Malaysia on November 13-16.
</P>
<P>
While APEC's work programs for 1998 would continue to focus on
the implementation of various strategies and action plans, they
must also take into account the higher expectations of such
programs to assist member economies in achieving sustainable
growth and equitable development, she said.
</P>
<P>
A number of APEC members such as Malaysia and Indonesia have
been facing economic problems since last July following
speculative attacks on their currencies.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah stressed there was a need to further raise the profile
of the development aspects of APEC cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, as the host for the next informal meeting of APEC
leaders this year, would emphasize on capacity building to enable
members, especially developing economies, to benefit more fully
from liberalization within APEC, she said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia would work closely with other APEC economies on
developing initiatives in human resource development and
technology and on broadening the outreach to a wider segment of
business, she said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will continue to work towards the implementation of
the APEC Small and Medium Enterprise (SME) framework and its
attendant programs to help these firms progress by addressing the
challenges of skills, knowledge and access to technologies, she
added.
</P>
<P>
The APEC region has about 40 million small and medium-scale
firms, which account for 90 percent of total companies and provide
nearly 80 percent of jobs in the region.
</P>
<P>
APEC economies account for 46 percent of global trade in 1996,
with exports totaling 2.3 trillion U.S. dollars and imports 2.5
trillion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
