<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Moves to Revamp Prisons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has set up a special
fund to help revamp prisons through agriculture and industrial
schemes, home affairs minister Peter Machungwa said here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted him as saying that the fund is
one of the solutions to the problem of inadequate resources to
run prisons.
</P>
<P>
When he opened a crime seminar he said the special fund will
get money from the already existing "government innovative fund".
</P>
<P>
"It is hoped that after this exercise the prisons services
would generate enough resources for sustaining prison operations
and imparting vocational skills to prisoners for use after
discharge," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told the delegates that it is now an accepted fact that
imprisonment is not an effective means of preventing crime and
non-custodial sentences should be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
"Inherent imprisonment is problem relating to prisoners'
re-socialization, formation of prison sub-cultures and prisoners'
stigmatization. These problems militate against successful
prison-based rehabilitation schems," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the world is beset by violence, social conflicts and
other forms of serious crime and "what is required, as a
foundation of new policy framework, is a new way of looking at
crime. This should involve shifting from an exclusive emphasis of
crime control to crime prevention."
</P>
<P>
The seminar is attended by heads of police from Zimbabwe,
Malawi, South Africa, Tanzania, Lesotho, Mozambique, Namibia and
Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
