<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Congo (K) to Cooperate in Mining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Anglo American, South
Africa's largest corporation, has pledged to join hands with
Gecamines, Democratic Gongo's state-owned mining company, to mine
in this central African country's Kolwezi area.
</P>
<P>
A consortium deal to the effect had been signed by the two
mining giants recently.
</P>
<P>
Foreign mining companies from Australia, Belgium, Canada and
China have also signed the deal. Anglo is expected to take a 15
percent stake, local daily Business Day quoted Anglozi officials
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The deal is said to cover 22,000 square kilometers of the
copper-rich Katanga area and involve the rehabilitation of large
open-pit mines and dumps.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Kolwezi mine workings hold about 1.44
million tons of copper and 275,000 tons of cobalt, worth about 10
billion U.S. Dollars. 
