<HEADLINE> Britain to Help Philippines Address El Nino Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A British water trade mission
will visit the Philippines next week to help the Southeast Asian
country address its water problems brought by the El Nino
phenomenon, the British embassy in Manila said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from 16 British companies will pay a visit to
the Philippines from January 25 to 31, the embassy said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the delegates will meet Philippine government
officials and private sector representatives to share expertise in
managing water resources and dealing with water leakages, as well
as their advanced water supply technology.
</P>
<P>
Paul Horton, the British Water Mission manager, said: "Over the
last 20 years, British Water members have developed close working
relationships with the Philippine government and industry."
</P>
<P>
"British companies are eager to demonstrate their advanced
water and waste water products, expertise and knowledge to the
Philippines as it prepares itself to tackle the serious effects of
El Nino," He said.
</P>
<P>
Since last March, most part of the Philippines has been
affected by the El Nino phenomenon and suffering from severe water
shortages. In the capital Manila, water supply has been cut by 60
percent for the past three months and the situation is unlikely to
be improved before the rainy season starts in July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
