<HEADLINE> Kenyan Nurses, Laboratory Staff Call off Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan nurses and laboratory
staff in the civil service have called off their two-month-old
strike to facilitate on-going negotiations between them and the
government,
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Wednesday, National all-Cadre
Nurses Union of Kenya, National Steering Committee and
Association of Medical Laboratory and Scientific Officers asked
their members countrywide to resume work immediately.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the striking employees said that the
newly-appointed Health Minister Jackson Kalweo initiated dialogue
last Friday and had shown total commitment to seek a solution to
their grievances.
</P>
<P>
They decided to suspend the strike to facilitate the dialogue
between an 11-man committee comprising nurses and laboratory
technicians, and top officials of the Health Ministry, the
statement noted.
</P>
<P>
Health Ministry officials welcomed the move and assured that
there would be no victimization and nurses' grievances would be
addressed before the end of April this year.
</P>
<P>
More than 30,000 nurses started their strike on November 28
last year to demand salary increments of between 200 and 500
percent, and laboratory technicians joined a few days later.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kenyan government did not meet their demands and
earlier this month sacked the striking health workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
