<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Combat Bhang Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has vowed to
demolish all bhang plants grown by several tribes in the southern
highland regions in order to eradicate drug consumption.
</P>
<P>
An official with the National Anti-Drugs Commission, George
Timbuka, told a press conference Wednesday that although drug
consumption in Tanzania has not reached alarming levels, the
commission is taking precautionary measures to prevent the
country from "jumping on the music wagon of drug trafficking."
</P>
<P>
The commission has realized that many people, especially in
the southern highlands, were consuming bhang as ingredients in
their food from time to time unaware of their side-effects to
health, Timbuka said.
</P>
<P>
"These people must be told that it is dangerous to eat such
kind of leaves and be educated on the legal implications of using
them," the official was quoted by Daily News as saying.
</P>
<P>
A research done in the bhang growing areas has revealed that
people there were more hostile than those in areas with the
plant, a member of the commission Professor Gad Paul Kilonzo told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a research conducted during 1995 and 1996 in Njombe
found that students in primary schools in bhang growing areas
were not performing as well as those in the areas without
producing the drug, Professor Kilonzo said.
</P>
<P>
The commission was formed under the Act of Drug and Prevention
of Illicit Trafficking of Drugs, which conforms to the 1988 UN
Convention against illicit trafficking and psychotropic
substances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
