<HEADLINE> Harare Situation Back to Normal: Police Assures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's police have assured
the public and businesses that the security situation in the
capital of Harare has improved and that they should operate as
usual starting this morning.
</P>
<P>
Following the moving in of the army to help police restore law
and order in the city and Chitungwiza's troubled high-density
suburbs, police said all was calm and advised the public to
ignore any suggestions to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
Police and the army would provide guards at all shopping
centers to ward off any looters and people in Harare and
Chitungwiza near Harare in particular, should not panic.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Superintendent Wayne Bvudzijena said last
night, "retail outlets are being encouraged to open and start
selling to the public as the situation has now reverted to
normal."
</P>
<P>
He said, "where there is no visible police or army presence,
shop owners should contact their nearest police station for the
provision of armed guards."
</P>
<P>
Some shops had opened in the city center yesterday morning.
But they closed mid-morning after rumors started circulating that
the situation was getting worse.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the rumors, the city center was peaceful for most
of the day yesterday. Police and the army maintained a heavy
presence.
</P>
<P>
The police public relations section from central Harare
embarked yesterday afternoon on a "hope restoration" campaign to
enable the public to realize that there was no more need to
panic.
</P>
<P>
In the past three days, thousands of residents in Harare,
Chitungwiza and Mutare staged demonstrations in protest against
recent prices increases.
</P>
<P>
Some of them looted shops, stoned cars and destroyed property,
causing billions of dollars losses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
