<HEADLINE> Samoan Leaders Reaffirm "One China" Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Samoan leaders have said that
the South Pacific nation will adhere to its "One China" policy and
would not conduct any official exchange with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
During separate meetings with visiting Chinese foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation Minister Wu Yi on Wednesday, Samoan Head
of State Malietoa Tanumafili and Prime Minister Tofilau Eti
Alesana said Samoa attaches great importance to its relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yi expressed her appreciation for the firm stand of the
Samoan government on the issue of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who arrived in Samoa on Tuesday, is the first Chinese
foreign trade minister to visit the South Pacific country since
the two countries established diplomatic relations 23 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister also held talks with Samoan Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance and Trade Minister Tuilaepa Sailele and
Transport Minister Joachim Keil on bilateral relations and trade
and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Samoan leaders thanked China for the economic assistance it
has provided over the past years, and expressed their confidence
in economic and trade cooperation between the two countries. They
also promised to encourage Samoa's private sector to develop
mutually beneficial economic cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Wu said China would do what it could to continue its economic
assistance to the island nation.
</P>
<P>
Wu said her visit was aimed at deepening mutual understanding,
promoting friendship and expanding cooperation so as to achieve
common development.
</P>
<P>
Samoa was one of the first few countries in the South Pacific
to establish diplomatic ties with China and the Chinese government
has been attaching great importance to the development of the
friendly cooperative relations between the two nations, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
During her talks with Samoan leaders, the Chinese foreign trade
minister gave an account of China's aircraft and shipbuilding
industries and expressed the hope that the two countries would
expand their cooperation in these fields.
</P>
<P>
Wu leaves for home on Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
