<HEADLINE> Chang Out, Rafter Through in Open Second Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Third-seeded Michael Chang of
the United States became the highest seed being toppled at the
Australian Open, while second seed Pat Rafter scraped into the
third round on Thursday in Melbourne, Australia.
</P>
<P>
Chang, world number three, was stunned by Frenchman Guillaume
Raoux in straight sets, 6-4, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-5), while the
Australian big-serve came back twice to grab a five-set win over
Todd Martin of the United States, 2-6, 7-6 (7-2), 6-7 (4-7), 6-4,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
Chang, who never won Australian Open and never won any grand
slam since 1989 when he took his first French Open championship,
could not keep up with the pace of his 46th-ranked opponent when
he dropped the match in straight.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Raoux, who was 4-14 on break point, won the
clash on his 12th ace to set Chang packed.
</P>
<P>
Chang is the seventh men's seed fell out of the Open so far
alongside with Carlos Moya, Thomas Muster, Sergi Bruguera, Goran
Ivanisevic, Mark Philippousses and Tim Henman.
</P>
<P>
Raoux's next rival will be either Wayne Black of Zimbabwe or
Michael Tebbutt of Australia.
</P>
<P>
World number two Rafter dropped the first set before the last
year's U.S. Open champion held onto a tie-breaker in the second.
</P>
<P>
Martin, runner-up in 1994 Open, took the next, but saw his
opponent got back onto his foot to win the last two to end the
marathon under temperatures over 40 Celsius. 
</P>
</TEXT>
