<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Ready to Join European Monetary Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Rudolf Edlinger, Austrian
Minister of Finance, announced Wednesday that his country has met
the requirements set in the Maastricht Treaty for joining the
Monetary Union of Europe, both in terms of budget deficit and debt.
</P>
<P>
According to Edlinger, the Austrian budget deficit in 1997
accounted for 2.7 percent of its gross domestic product (GDP), 0.3
percent lower than the required 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's public debt accounted for 66.5 percent of the GDP
in 1997, compared with the previous 69.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Edlinger said the decline in debt met the requirement of
joining the monetary union, although the percentage rate was still
higher than the required 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian budget deficit in 1997 was 67.2 billion schillings
(84 million U.S. dollars), 800 million schillings less than the
planned budget deficit. The public debt decreased 38.3 billion
schillings (48 million dollars) to 1.47 trillion schillings (1.8
billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit decrease was a result of the Austrian
government's drive to cut expenses in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Edlinger said that in the coming two years, the Austrian
government will subsidize the budget by privatization.
</P>
<P>
Austria acquired 17.8 billion schillings (22 million dollars)
in 1997 by selling national property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0222 </DOCNO>
