<HEADLINE> S.Lanka Cancels Tender for Traffic Signal Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Transport and
Highways Minister A.H.M. Fowzie has canceled an international
tender for the supply and construction of computerized traffic
signal systems in the country, ministry officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the move on the ground that local expertise
was capable of implementing the project at one fourth of the cost
estimated by the World Bank (WB).
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, which is funding the project, said the cost
could be 21 million Rupees (338,710 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The officials said the transportation engineering division of
the Moratuwa University, the Road Development Authority and the
Colombo Municipal Council have started designing the project.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the one that was put into use in the central
mountain city of Kandy Tuesday, the ministry plans to install 30
more such systems in the country by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry hopes to establish a computerized link throughout
the country to monitor and regulate traffic flows.
</P>
<P>
Traffic jams have become increasingly a headache in many
cities, especially in the capital Colombo. Police sources have
said that half of the travel time on road is wasted due to traffic
congestion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
