<HEADLINE> Italian PM Visits Macedonia to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romanno
Prodi arrived in Skopje, capital of Macedonia, Wednesday for a
one-day visit to boost bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who is the first Italian prime minister to visit
Macedonia since it proclaimed its independence from Yugoslavia in
1991, met Macedonia President Kiro Gligorov, parliament speaker
Tito Petkovski and Prime Minister Branko Crvenkovski.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Gligorov, Prodi appreciated Macedonia's role
in maintaining peace and stability in the Balkan region. He said
Italy stands for positive cooperation with the Balkan states and
that Macedonia can serve as a bridge of cooperation between Italy
and Oriental countries.
</P>
<P>
Gligorov said his country is applying for membership of the
European Union and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Italy
has given its support and help in this aspect, and Macedonia
expects Italy to continue providing such help in its application
process, he added.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the two countries signed a protocol on debt
payment rescheduling. Italy would cut Macedonia's arrears of 11.38
million U.S. dollars to 9 million dollars and provide a
preferential loan to the former Yugoslav member.
</P>
<P>
Italy is the sixth largest trading partner of Macedonia.
</P>
</TEXT>
