<HEADLINE> Police Unrest in Albania Cools Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A police unrest in Shkodra, a
large town in northern Albania, cooled down Wednesday afternoon,
Albanian news media reported.
</P>
<P>
The armed rebel policemen, who captured the Shkodra government
building for more than a day, withdrew at 4:50 p.m. local time and
the tension tended to calm.
</P>
<P>
Key organs of the town and major state highways were under
control of the local police and the commandos coming from Tirana.
</P>
<P>
Many schools in Shkodra were still closed due to security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
The governor, Gezim Podgorica, who was held hostage by the
rebels for 24 hours in the government building, told the press
that he decided to step down because he was actually unable to
carry out his duties.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Shkodra, a strong base of the largest
opposition party, the Democratic Party, remained strained in
recent days when the Interior Ministry dismissed and replaced the
town's police chief and dispatched a group of commandos.
</P>
<P>
The riot broke out when the new police chief started an
investigation into a number of smuggling and robbery cases in
which some local policemen were involved.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party accused the government of making
vindictive attacks on the opposition and called for the withdrawal
of the new police chief and his commandos to avoid more clashes.
</P>
<P>
In return, the ruling Socialist Party charged the local
Democratic Party leader of provoking the riot and asked law
enforcement agencies to check into all anti-government
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
