<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Court Backs Parents' Right to Discipline Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 21 (Xinhua) -- An American couple in
Oakland, California, were told Tuesday that they had the right to
ship their son to a rehabilitation school in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
Jim Van Blarigan and his wife were satisfied with the ruling of
a Superior Court judge, saying that it was in their son's best
interest. Other parents left the Alameda County courtroom with
relief because they also sent their children overseas to
behavior-modification programs.
</P>
<P>
The Oakland case has got national attention because it involved
the rights of minors as well as parents, an issue that have been
debated in the United States for decades.
</P>
<P>
Each year thousands of American teenagers are spirited away to
programs to be disciplined. For many heavy hearted parents who are
at their wits' end on how to deal with their defiant or
drug-addicted children, the programs, including adolescent
psychiatric hospitals, behavior-modification schools, residential
treatment centers, wilderness camps and boot camps, offer the last
hope.
</P>
<P>
In most cases, the teenagers are taken away from home by
moonlighting cops, bounty hunters or probation officers, who are
permitted by parents to use any means necessary. Those escorts
usually charge 2,500 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Child advocates oppose escort services, referring to them as
"kidnappers" and to the teen's involuntary removal as "abduction."
</P>
<P>
In the Oakland case, the 16-year-old high school student was
taken away from bed at midnight by two men hired by his
parents. He was driven 700 miles (about 1,000 kilometers) in a
locked car to a private adolescent hospital for an evalution and
then taken to Jamaica. His parents said that he has a discipline
problem.
</P>
<P>
Legal experts say that the ruling of the case would affect
other families, especially in California, who are seeking similar
treatment for their troubled or troublesome children. It is
believed that thousands of California teen have been sent out of
state over the years. Most are white, and middle to upper
class. Some private centers cost 100,000 for a two-year residential
program usually in Utah or Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
Once parents send their "out of control" kids away, they
usually tell only relatives and close friends because they feel
ashamed and embarrassed. But they have no other way out -- those
programs are their last resort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
