<HEADLINE> Russia, Georgia to Improve Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze said Wednesday there was no irresolvable issue in his
country's relations with Russia, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press in Tbilisi after meeting Yegor Stroyev,
speaker of the Russian Federation Council, the parliament's upper
house, Shevardnadze said "bugs" in bilateral ties are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
The complicated part of the Georgian-Russian relations, he
said, was that they once were in the same union, thus calling for
a new type of relationship to resolve all disputes between the two.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Stroyev said a treaty signed four years ago by
Russian and Georgian presidents on forging bilateral relations of
friendly cooperation will be approved by Russia's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian parliament ratified the treaty on January 1997.
</P>
<P>
As about whether Russian peacekeepers in Abkhazia, Georgia,
would stay after their mandate expires on January 31, Stroyev said
it will depend on the attitude and stand of the Georgian side.
</P>
<P>
A military conflict in the western Georgian region broke out in
August 1992 when the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia declared
itself a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Georgian President Shevardnadze and the
Abkhazian leadership, Russian peacekeeping troops entered Abkhazia
in mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze said recently the Russian troops should leave
unless they protect the return of Georgian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Stroyev arrived in Tbilisi Wednesday for a two-day visit.
During his talks with Shevardnadze, he passed on the views of
Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Russian-Georgian ties.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said Russia will make its best endeavors to strengthen
the friendly relations between Russia and Georgia, and solve all
problems between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
