<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Book Publishers in Indonesia Facing Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Of the 480 book publishers in
Indonesia, only 200 are still productive due to increasing prices
of paper, especially newsprint, following the dramatic fall of the
rupiah (national currency), local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A discussion on books held here Wednesday concluded that only
200 book publishers can still maintain their production
activities. However, unless prices of paper begin to decline
immediately, it is estimated that only 100 book publishers will
still be active by March this year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Book Publishers Association Chairman Rozali Usman
said at the discussion that many book publishers have decided to
halt production because of high prices of paper.
</P>
<P>
The price of paper has risen from 2,000 rupiah per kilogram to
6,000 rupiah per kilogram in the local market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the price of newsprint has increased from 1,254
rupiah per kilogram in January 1997 to the present 3,252.3 rupiah
per kilogram, an increase of 235.56 percent in one year.
</P>
<P>
Aside from paper, prices of other materials like ink and film,
which mostly still have to be imported, have also increased as a
result of the rupiah's depreciation against the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
In this situation, many newspapers in the country have been
forced to reduce the number of their pages or raise their prices.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Loans Opened to Non-State Enterprises in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Non-State enterprises in China
now can get policy-oriented loans, which are no longer the only
privilege of State-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Export and Import Bank of China (Eximbank), one of the
three policy-oriented banks, has decided to gradually expand its
financial services to collectively-owned firms and joint-stock
companies as well as some foreign-funded enterprises from this
year, today's China Daily quoted bank chairman Tong Zhiguang as
saying.
</P>
<P>
These non-State companies will mainly be manufacturers and
exporters of machinery and electronic products, which corresponds
to the Eximbank's target in underpinning China's exports of
high-tech and high value-added capital goods.
</P>
<P>
"There is no more restriction on the non-State companies
getting financial support," said Gu Mingchao, vice-president of
Eximbank. But "the large and medium-sized State-owned firms will
remain as major clients."
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to those profitable machinery and
electronic firms with products having market potential, such as
ships, telecommunications and electronic products.
</P>
<P>
Machinery and electronic products are currently the largest
export category of China with their export volume reaching 59.3
billion yuan (7.14 billion U.S. dollars) last year, representing
32 percent of China's total exports.
</P>
<P>
But exports of high-tech items are a slight proportion of the
overall machinery and electronic exports, indicating a big
potential for growth.
</P>
<P>
The Eximbank now mainly offers export credit, insurance and
guarantees to facilitate Chinese machinery and electronic
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
