<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Govt Increases Funds for Industrial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
allocated a sum of 2.5 billion Rupees (40.3 million U.S.
dollars)for industrial development this year, 19 percent up from
2.1 billion Rupees (33.9 million dollars) in 1997, officials of
the Industrial Development Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used to improve the existing industries as
well as to offer incentives to investors to set up new
enterprises, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Part of the funds will be used to promote the proposed garment
factories program, which aims to further boost the sector by
setting up 50 more factories throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry used the majority of last year's funds to develop
industrial estates, strengthen productivity enhancement and
industrial restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The officials also said the industrial export sector recorded
significant results in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Garments and textiles accounted for 30 percent of the foreign
exchange earnings last year. The sector earned 120 billion Rupees
(1.94 billion dollars) from January to November last year,
compared with 92 billion Rupees (1.48 billion dollars) in the same
period the previous year. 
</P>
