<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspected Students to Be Drug-Tested in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Education Ministry
will soon work out regulations to conduct drug tests on those
school- children suspected of drug use, according to the Nation
newspaper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Government schools will soon be instructed to categorize their
students in four groups -- non-drug users, drug addicts, recent
drug addicts or those at risk, and members of drug-trade rings,
said Prime Minister's Office Minister Jurin Laksanavisit
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The schools will also implement anti-drug measures and provide
rehabilitation programs, with assistance from the Education
Ministry and the Office of the Narcotics Control Board.
</P>
<P>
Teachers and school managers will face tough legal action and
harsh penalties if they are found guilty of involvement in selling
drugs in their schools, said Jurin.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are about 260,000 to 300,000
students addicted to narcotics in schools ranging from primary to
university level in 30 of the country's 76 provinces surveyed, and
that 80 percent of them are new users.
</P>
<P>
Students in vocational schools make up the largest percentage
of drug users, while the second largest are those in secondary
schools, according to an official of the Office of the Narcotics
Control Board.  
</P>
</TEXT>
