<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile, Canada Sign Tax Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Chile and Canada signed an
agreement here Wednesday to prevent tax evasion and double
taxation on income and property tax.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Chilean President Eduardo Frei and
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien who arrived here on Tuesday
for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The accord, together with the free trade agreement signed by
the two nations in November 1996, will provide an additional
incentive for investments between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also signed a memorandum of understanding on
educational cooperation and a statement of intentions on
cooperation in scientific research and technology.
</P>
<P>
Chretien is touring Latin America with a delegation comprised
of provincial premiers, two federal ministers and 400 businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Chile, the Canadian businessmen visited
Mexico, Brazil and Argentina; they also signed trade, cultural and
scientific exchange agreements.
</P>
<P>
Canada is an important foreign investor for Chile with major
investments in mining. By September 1997, The total amount of
Canadian investments amounted to 3.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Chile exported more than 138 million dollars worth of
merchandise to Canada and imported 258 million dollars of products.
</P>
<P>
Chilean exports to Canada reached 73.5 million dollars in
July-December 1997, a 60 percent increase over the same period in
1996, while imports increased 29 percent to 253.5 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
