<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Hit by Country-wide Power Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 22 (Xinhua) -- A nation-wide power failure hit
Sri Lanka Wednesday afternoon, a second such incident in less than
two months, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Electricity supply was shut down at around 1:00 PM and was
restored only one and a half hours later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ceylon Electricity Board (CEB) attributed the power failure
to a technical problem in its power control system. The problem
had not been identified until Wednesday evening, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
A senior CEB official was quoted as saying that virtually the
whole country was out of power, except a few places.
</P>
<P>
Heavy traffic built up in Colombo city and its suburbs as all
the traffic lights failed to function.
</P>
<P>
This was the second similar incident in less than two months.
</P>
<P>
On December 5, 1997, an island-wide electricity failure plunged
Sri Lanka into a total darkness for at least 70 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent to the electricity failure, telecommunications were
down for almost three hours, making it impossible for customers of
local telecommunications services to establish international
direct dial (IDD) connection with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The CEB said the large-scale blackout was due to a technical
defect at a power station in Norton Bridge in the central mountain
area of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
