<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ad Campaign Launched to Urge Ban on "Soft Money" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A 1 million-dollar ad
campaign was launched on Wednesday urging the U.S. Congress to ban
so-called "soft-money" political contributions.
</P>
<P>
"Soft money" -- donations to political parties to be used for
generic party-building activities such as get-out-the-vote drives
and not for candidates -- is a central issue of the campaign
reform.
</P>
<P>
Campaign for America, founded by Wall Street financier Jerome
Kohlberg, began running a 30-second ad on cable television
stations in nine states that were chosen because their Republican
senators might be persuaded to support legislation that would ban
soft money, said Douglas Berman, the group's president.
</P>
<P>
The ad is running in Arkansas, Colorado, Iowa, Kansas,
Michigan, Mississippi, New Hampshire, New York and Ohio, The
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of a bipartisan campaign bill named for Senators
John McCain, a Republican, and Russell Feingold, a Democrat,
couldn't muster sufficient votes to get it through the Senate last
fall. The measure would have banned soft money from presidential
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders in both the House of Representatives and
Senate promised debate and votes in the spring.
</P>
<P>
The TV spot and others to be produced will run through
February. The group also took out ads in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
The TV spot shows a man and women sitting at a kitchen table
going over bills when a voice comes on saying "corporate polluters
and tobacco companies... get big tax breaks in exchange for huge
political contributions."
</P>
<P>
Critics say donors give soft money to influence lawmakers'
decisions about policies and regulations that affect their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
"These ads give a sense that there is a connection between very
large corporate gifts and policy outcomes," said Berman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
