<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Contributes to Chinese Province's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 22 (Xinhua) -- One fifth of the investment in
fixed assets in northeast China's Liaoning Province was from
abroad, Vice-Governor Gao Guozhu said here recently.
</P>
<P>
The province has used 13 billion U.S. dollars in the 1992-97
period, making up 21.8 percent of its total investment in fixed
assets, Gao said at a conference on the use of foreign investment
in the province.
</P>
<P>
A total of 6,000 foreign-funded firms started operation in
Liaoning in the past six years, yielding a combined output value
of 270 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of foreign-funded firms'industrial output value
in the province's total has risen from five percent in
1992 to the present 17 percent. Foreign-funded enterprises have
offered jobs for 600,000 local residents, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
The use of foreign funds has expanded from previous processing
trade to petrol-chemical, metallurgical, machinery, electronic,
agricultural, energy, infrastructural and financial industries.
</P>
<P>
The port city of Dalian has attracted half of the overseas
investment of Liaoning. Two thirds of the remainers were used in
Shenyang, the provincial capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
