<HEADLINE> Russia Aims at Nine Golds on Winter Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia was aiming at nine golds
in the upcoming Winter Olympic Games, and laying their hopes much
upon events like cross-country skiing, biathlon and figure
skating, said a major official of the Russian team.
</P>
<P>
Victor Mamatov, chief executive of the representative team
namely the "Nagano-98", told a press conference here that a total
of 126 athletes, competing all the events except women's ice
hockey, curling and snowboarding, would like to see their goal
fulfilled in February in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Maratov said Russians were also seeking for medals in speed
skating and icy hockey sessions besides events the Russians are
firmly strong.
</P>
<P>
But figure skaters and figure skiers were to confound double
contest in the Games, referring to the problem of referees,
Maratov added.
</P>
<P>
Maratov said the referees of events, like figure skating and
figure skiing, in which the Russians are hot favorites, can't make
objective judgement regardless race and nationality.
</P>
<P>
Maratov added that he had make an appeal to Juan Antonio
Samaranch, president of the International Olympic Committee (IOC),
and looked forward to big progress in Nagano. 
</P>
