<HEADLINE> China's Soybean Imports to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China's imports of soybean will
keep surging up this year when the soybean price on the
international market turns down, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to import 3.7 million tons of soybean this
year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Customs indicate imports of soybeans jumped
138 percent to 2.03 million tons in the first 11 months of 1997,
compared with the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of imports in 1997 is expected to have reached
three million tons, accounting for 18 percent of domestic soybean
consumption.
</P>
<P>
China, a soybean exporter three years ago, is estimated to have
consumed 16.5 million tons of soybean last year while total
domestic output was 13.34 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Farmers prefer to plant corn rather than soybean as the profit
margin on corn is bigger. The area under soybean had shrunk
from 122.1 million hectares in 1995 to 112.1 million hectares last
year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the total output of soybean this year will
maintain the same level as last year.
</P>
<P>
The soybean price on the international market is expected to
fall from the current 275 US dollars per ton.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
