<HEADLINE> Land Use Ban Instrumental to Inspection, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China's one-year freeze on the
use of arable land for non-agricultural purposes, introduced last
April, was instrumental to concluding a nationwide inspection of
farmland so used since 1991, an official was quoted as saying by
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Based on the result of the inspection, the government has
moved toward improving land management by drafting an overall
utilization plan and revising its existing Land Mangement Law,
Zou Yuchuan, director of the State Land Administration said.
</P>
<P>
The effort has also produced a new figure on China's cultivated
land, which will be publicized this year when the statistics are
verified by a detailed survey of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Although the new farmland figure may be a little higher than
the existing official figure of about 100 million hectares, the
situation that China has to feed 22 percent of the world's
population with less than 10 percent of the world's arable land
remains critical, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He noted the one-year freeze on the use of arable land, which
was officially decreed by the State Council, will continue
this year. The extended freeze will also cover the
suspension of power of counties in land-use approval, and the
prevention of more land from being occupied by urban expansion
projects.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, about 2.02 million hectares had been
occupied by a variety of non-agricultural projects since 1991, and
half of these were cultivated farmland.
</P>
<P>
The inspection, the largest since the mid-1980s, has helped the
government know the exact amount of non-agricultural land-use,
land-use potential and how to regulate the land market.
</P>
<P>
During the check, 116,000 hectares were found to have been left
idle or used ineffciently. Nearly 54 percent of the figure was
cultivated land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
