<HEADLINE> Offshore Fishing Ban to Be Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- China is considering extending
the absolute ban on offshore fishing from two months to three
months this year in a bid to preserve marine resources.
</P>
<P>
The moratorium area will also be expanded, an official from the
Ministry of Agriculture was quoted as saying by today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has submitted the report to the State Council and
is waiting for approval.
</P>
<P>
The ban would begin on June 16 and end on September 15,
compared with July 1 to August 31, the restricted period in the
past three years.
</P>
<P>
And the moratorium area will be expanded southward from 27
degrees to 26 degrees north latitude. The northern boundary would
continue to be 35 degrees north latitude.
</P>
<P>
This will be the fourth year of the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
From September 1 to October 31, fishing is allowed only beyond
30 nautical miles offshore in those areas. During that period,
when the fish were still not mature enough, the ban limited the
proportion of immature fish caught to no more than 25 percent of
each catch.
</P>
<P>
Fishery output in these areas has increased annually in the
past three years as a result of the moratorium. Major fish species
in China's sea areas, such as the hairtail, have grown larger and
bigger thanks to the ban.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cassava output to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Cassava production in Thailand
for the 1997-98 crop is expected to be dropped by 19 percent from
the previous year, to 14.33 million tons, according to the Thai
Tapioca Development Institute.
</P>
<P>
Chalaw Fuangaromya, president of the institute, attributed the
drop to drought in Northeastern Thailand which hit the main
cassava-planting areas, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some planters have turned away from cassava to
grow crops that fetch better prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
The smaller output of the new crop, which will be release to
the market in September, is expected to result in prices of
cassava roots rising to between 1.20 and 1.40 baht a kilogram,
compared with 0.80 baht last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
