<HEADLINE> Philippines to Seek 2.7 Billion Dollars from IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is ready to
start exploratory talks with the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
for 2.7 billion U.S. dollars to shore up its foreign exchange
reserve.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper the Business Daily reported on Thursday that
the facility may take effect after the country exits form the
IMF's 35 years of economic supervision.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at the second quarter. It's a standby facility.
We can draw against it if the currency situation continued to be
difficult," Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The currency turmoil in Asia had reduced the Philippines' gross
international reserve to about 9 billion dollars at the end of
last year from a peak of 12 billion dollars prior to the
devaluation of the peso last July.
</P>
<P>
"It is a starting point of discussion with the IMF. Whether it
is going to be that or not, we will see at the end of the
negotiations," de Ocampo added.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is finishing a three-year IMF program by the
end of the month, the last of a series of IMF-prescribed programs
over the past 35 years aimed at weaning the country away from
dependence on foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the IMF, the Philippine government is also
negotiating for between 500 million and 600 million U.S. dollars
in loans from the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Santiago Subway Carries More Passengers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A total of 200 million
passengers rode on the Santiago subways in 1997, 11.9 percent more
than in 1996, an official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Daniel Fernandez, chairman of the Board of Metro, S.A., a
company that operates subways in the city, said the Santiago
subway gained a net profit of 1.2 billion pesos (around 2.6
million U.S. dollars) last year, a 20 percent decrease in revenues
compared to the preceding fiscal period.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was attributed to an additional 3.3 billion pesos
(about 7 million dollars) used in the construction of a new subway
line.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chile's subway system, together with those of Hong
Kong and Singapore, is one of only three in the world whose costs
are covered by the operation.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, a total of 197 million dollars will be invested in
technological innovations, maintenance to subway trains and
construction of the extension line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
