<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Farmers in China to Be Self-Reliant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Foundation for
Underdeveloped Regions of China (FURC) is to sponsor projects for
more destitute farmers to become self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
The FURC is a non-governmental organization established in 1989 to
help China's poor regions.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, FURC's projects aim to help
the poor gain a means of living by improving their farming
environment.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yuzhao, FURC's vice-president, said that now the
foundation is working on three programs to help poverty-stricken
farmers become better off.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the mountainous area of southwest China's
Guizhou Province, people are blasting away rock to create arable
land of 667 hectares.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 people there will gain precious arable land and
become self-sufficient in grain by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, more scientific and technological training
is to be conducted this year so that farmers can make better use
of the resources available, he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 people have attended the training courses
sponsored by the FURC since 1994.
</P>
<P>
One of FURC's subjects is to help farmers to grow edible
fungi. Now training courses on raising fungi are being offered
in Beijing to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Since 1989, the FURC has invested 400 million yuan (48.2 million
U.S. dollars) in poverty relief projects.
</P>
<P>
More than 60,000 people across the country have benefited from
FURC's programs, and 30,000 of them acquired a means of farming and
become self-reliant.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
