<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese PLA Commander Helps 200,000 People Become Well-Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Peng Chuzheng, a commander of
the People's Liberation Army, has helped 200,000 people in central
China's Hunan Province to become well-off in the past 14 years.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita income of the farmers in western Hunan, one of
China's impoverished areas, has increased to 980 yuan (118
U.S. dollars) a year from 300 yuan (36 U.S. dollars) 14 years
ago. People living below the poverty line have been reduced from
1.56 million to 360,000.
</P>
<P>
Peng started his poverty relief program in 1984 under the
direction of leaders of the Jishou Autonomous Prefecture of Hunan,
where his army was stationed.
</P>
<P>
He led his men in building houses, water conservation and
irrigation facilities, and schools for the poor, while introducing
advanced agricultural techniques to increase grain output.
</P>
<P>
Peng and his men have built houses for 70,000 local poor
people, and rebuilt 502 schools for 53,000 children, and 310,000
people now have an adequate supply of drinking water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
