<HEADLINE> Ancient Opera Stage Discovered in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered the ruins of an 860-year-old opera stage in Zhenjiang
city in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The stage dates back to the Southern Song Dynasty (1127-1279),
the archeologists say.
</P>
<P>
The ruins were beneath a stage built in the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The archeologists have unearthed many relics of wall structure
and building materials of the Southern Song Dynasty after moving
away the Qing Dynasty stage.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jianguo, director of the Zhenjiang Archeology Institute, said
that the stage was destroyed in a fire in the Yuan Dynasty
(1271-1368), and was rebuilt on its base in the Yuan and Qing
dynasties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
