<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Hits Argentine Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Argentina's exports of
cereals and grains this year will be hit by the financial crisis
in Asian countries which are the markets for a large portion of
its agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
A study released Wednesday by a prestigious consulting firm
said this year's income from cereal and oil grain exports will
drop by more than two billion dollars compared to the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
This will account for a 25 percent decrease in the total annual
exports of agricultural products of Argentina, which in recent
years averaged around 7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Up to January 16, 1998, corn exporters have only closed sales
for 700,000 tons, while by the same date last year, they had
already signed contracts for over 2.5 million tons, which means
that income of over 1.1 billion dollars has been lost.
</P>
<P>
Up to the same date this year, wheat exporters have only been
able to sell 3.5 million tons, compared to 7.5 million tons by the
same date of last year, a decreased income of 750 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
With respect to oil grains, such as soy and sunflower seeds
which were targeted mainly to Asian countries, income losses
exceed 225 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Asian countries are the leading purchasers of Argentina's
agricultural products and the single product that will be hardest
hit is corn, since Argentina's annual corn exports are 4 million
tons, accounting for 10 percent of the imported products in that
region.
</P>
<P>
Analysts consider that other factors that have had a strong
impact on Argentine agricultural exports are the drop in the
prices of these products on international markets and the decrease
in oil prices, because the major oil exporters can no longer
afford to import the same quantities of agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, neighboring Brazil -- a major purchaser of
Argentina's cereals and oil grains -- is undergoing strenuous
economic adjustments and problems, which will clearly affect its
purchasing power and, therefore, the amounts it buys from
Argentina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0271 </DOCNO>
