<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Approves Proposals to Reduce Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 22 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines has approved two proposals submitted by the Bankers
Association to bring down interest rates, local press reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Central Bank has agreed to re-open its
30-day lending window and monetize the banks' government
securities holdings in a bid to cut the interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The lending window will allow the banks to avail of cheap funds
from the Central Bank and earn an interest rate spread high than
when they borrow overnight from each other.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the monetization of the government securities
holdings at market rates would allow the banks to easily liquefy
their assets, thus helping reduce the interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank also approved the request of oil companies and
exporters to be included in the currency risk protection program
of the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
With the approval, oil companies are now allowed to hedge their
dollar loans against forward contracts with the Central Bank. The
agreement assures the oil companies and exporters of a dollar
source and is expected to significantly reduce their speculative
activities in the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the government efforts to stabilize the exchange
rate of the peso, the banks' interest rates soared to 25-30
percent from the pre-devaluation level of 14-15 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
