<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, January 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U. S. President Bill Clinton said on Wednesday
that "something is going to give" in order to resolve the standoff
with Iraq over weapons inspections
</P>
<P>
He told PBS television in an interview that Iraq's refusal to
allow U.N. weapons inspectors to check its "presidential sites"
was "a very serious thing," and he would not rule out to take
military actions to force Iraq to fully and unconditionally abide
by the UN resolutions. (US-Iraq-Arms Inspection)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- In face of the widespread Asian financial crisis,
"our first job is clear: to help stabilize the immediate crisis,"
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at Georgetown University, Rubin also warned the
fallout "could be much greater" if the financial problems spread
to other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has enormously important economic and
national security interests at stake in promoting restoration of
financial stability in Asia," he said. "When we act to resolve the
Asian crisis, we act to protect and benefit the American people,"
he stressed. (US-Rubin-Asian Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- A senior South Korean financial representative met
here Wednesday with William McDonough, president of the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York, for talks on refinancing of the
short-term debt of the Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
"It's very much informative and constructive," said Yong Hwan
Kim, co-chairman of South Korea's joint Presidential Economic
Committee, who flew in New York Sunday heading a financial
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The main issues in the talks were the form of any South Korean
debt refinancing, what prices would be acceptable to Seoul and
international bankers, and whether Seoul should issue new debt,
sources close to the South Korean delegation said. (New
York-S.Korea-Bank Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Chairman of the Palestinian Authority Yasir
Arafat arrived in Washington Wednesday for talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton on the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader is expected to meet Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright this evening and then hold talks with Clinton
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said in Paris on his way to Washington that he pinned
his hope on the president for the progress of the peace process,
which has almost collapsed since last March because of Israel's
decision to build Jewish housing units in Arab East Jerusalem.
(US-Palestinians-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- A Catholic man in his min-50s was shot dead by gunmen
Wednesday afternoon as he sat in his car in a loyalist area of
Belfast, police said.
</P>
<P>
An eyewitness said he heard five shots and ran out to find the
man slumped in the car. The victim, shot in the chest and neck,
died in an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
The government condemned the murder and said the "gruesome"
shootings must stop. (UK-Belfast-Shooting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- A Russian envoy said here Wednesday that her country
would keep its promise to provide Cyprus with the S-300
anti-aircraft missiles this year.
</P>
<P>
Valentina Matvienko, Russia's women ambassador in Athens,
stressed that no threat from Turkey or any other country could
change Russia's decision to supply the missiles if Cyprus wanted
them.
</P>
<P>
Russia, she said, would find "the most appropriate way" to send
the missiles to Nicosia. (Russia-Cyprus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The Irish Republican Army issued a statement
Wednesday to reject the joint peace process document tabled by the
British and Irish governments last week.
</P>
<P>
The statement faxed to the BBC in Belfast said "responsibility
for undoing damage done to the prospects for a just and lasting
peace rests squarely with the British government."
</P>
<P>
It said Prime Minister Tony Blair has "succumbed to the Orange
card" and that the cease-fire is "not being matched by confidence
building measures from the government." (UK-IRA-Peace Process)
</P>
