<HEADLINE> Overseas-Funded Financial Institutions Make Greater Profits in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 22 (Xinhua) -- Profits of overseas-funded
financial institutions in this economic center of China jumped 28
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed here Tuesday by Mao Yingliang,
president of the Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of China,
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Mao, who declined to reveal the exact amount of profits made by
overseas-funded financial institutions, said that the profits of
Chinese commercial banks in Shanghai surged 29.9 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Currently Shanghai has 51 licensed overseas-funded financial
institutions and 162 representative offices. Eight overseas-funded
banks have been selected to deal in business in the Chinese currency
on a trial basis in the city's Pudong New Area, a rising financial
and trade district separated from downtown Shanghai by the
Huangpujiang River.
</P>
<P>
Mao said that this year Shanghai will continue to follow a
moderately tight monetary policy and beef up its pace in
establishing a modern financial system so as to lay a solid
foundation for Shanghai to be an international financial center in
the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
