<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybean, Crude Futures Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Corn and soybean futures
prices plunged on the Chicago Board of Trade (CBT)on Wednesday
amid concerns of increasing planting acreage and crude futures on
the New York Mercantile Exchange also sank for fears of falling
demand for oil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. forecasting firm predicted that corn acreage may rise to
81.749 million acres this Spring from 80.2 million in 1997 while
land under soybean may soar to a record 71.635 million acres from
70.9 million last year.
</P>
<P>
Good weather in corn and soybean growing countries in South
America also helped the market sentiment. Argentina is said to
boost its soybean production to 15.6 million tons instead of U.S.
prediction of 14.5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
CBT corn for March delivery lost 2 cents to 2.76 U.S. dollars a
bushel, March soybeans retreated 5 cents to 6.69 dollars a bushel.
</P>
<P>
NYME Crude futures fell to the lowest point since April 21,
1994, as Asia, affected by financial crisis, is predicted by the
International Energy Agency to cut oil demand by as much as
230,000 barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
March light sweet crude oil fell 26 cents or 1.6 percent to
16.30 dollars a barrel while the complex closed 20 cents lower at
16.36 dollars a barrel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
