<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S&AMP;P Affirms Boeing Ratings, Downgrades Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Standard &AMP; Poor's today
affirmed its rating on Boeing and related entities while revising
its outlook for the company to negative from stable.
</P>
<P>
Boeing's corporate credit was affirmed as AA+ among other
affirmations as S&AMP;P recognizes its prominent position within the
commercial aircraft manufacturing industry and favorable long-term
growth prospects for that business, S&AMP;P said in a press release on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It also pointed to the fact that Boeing has a leading position
in defense and space and a very strong financial profile
characterized by impressive cash flow generation, relatively low
debt usage and sizable cash balances.
</P>
<P>
The outlook revision reflects "serious economic and financial
problems in the Asia-Pacific market", S&AMP;P said.
</P>
<P>
The problems are expected to lead to deferral or cancellations
of airplane orders by some airlines, it added.
</P>
<P>
Most at risk are widebody aircraft, including B747s which
typically have higher profit margins.
</P>
<P>
There is also a likelihood of a decline in future orders,
because of a slowdown in air traffic growth in the region, S&AMP;P
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says He Would Not Rule Out Military Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- U. S. President Bill Clinton
said on Wednesday that "something is going to give" in order to
resolve the standoff with Iraq over weapons inspections
</P>
<P>
He told PBS television in an interview that Iraq's refusal to
allow U.N. weapons inspectors to check its "presidential sites"
was "a very serious thing," and he would not rule out to take
military actions to force Iraq to fully and unconditionally abide
by the UN resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"This is a serious thing with me, this is a very serious
thing," Clinton told PBS.
</P>
<P>
"I can't rule out any options, but I can tell you I am very
concerned about this," he said. "Sooner or later something is
going to give. I am just very much hoping that we can reason with
him (Iraqi President Saddam Hussein) before that happens. We've
got to have those sites open."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he preferred to apply diplomatic pressure
through the United Nations to make Iraq comply with U.N.
resolutions on weapons inspections, "but if they (Iraqis) really
believe there are no circumstances in which we would act alone
they are sadly mistaken. that is not a threat."
</P>
<P>
Earlier at a State Department briefing, spokesman James Rubin
told reporters that Iraq's proposal to freeze weapons
inspections on its "presidential sites" was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
"It appears Iraq has ignored the message of the U.N. Security
Council and instead tried to impose new and unacceptable
conditions on the U.N. operations," Rubin said at a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
Chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard Butler said in Baghdad
on Wednesday that Iraq had asked him to freeze attempts to
inspect "presidential sites" until a series of technical
evaluation talks on disarmament. Iraq proposed a meeting in
April to discuss further access.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Butler went to Baghdad "with a clear message from
the Security Council that Iraq must cooperate fully and
unconditionally with the U.N.".
</P>
<P>
Rubin reiterated U.S. preparedness to take military action to
force Iraq to comply with U.N. resolutions on dismantling
weapons of mass destruction, but said diplomatic channels were
still being pursued.
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Butler plans to brief the Security Council on
Friday. It's premature to speculate on what actions might be
taken until after he has had a chance to report fully on his
visit. But again, we are not ruling out any options," Rubin
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
