<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stock Falls Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street fell
sharply today as the world computer giant IBM issued an unusual
warning that its first-quarter profits would fall short, dragged
down by slack consumer demand in Asia and the strong dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 78 points to 7,794, a
partial recovery from a 135-point slide that briefly wiped out all
of Tuesday's 119-point rally.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market measures also surrendered a chunk of Tuesday's
gains, which put several indexes in back positive territory for
1998 for the first time since January 2.
</P>
<P>
Surprisingly, although IBM tumbled the equivalent of a more
than 30 Dow points, the technology sector suffered only a marginal
loss.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell only a little
bit more than a tenth of a percent.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advances by an 11-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,130 up, 1,787 down and 527
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 625.12 million shares vs. 638.92 million in
the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 7.82 to 970.78, and
the NYSE composite index fell 4.02 to 507.90.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 2.22 to 1,587.92, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.93 to 669.44.
</P>
