<HEADLINE> South Korean Representative Meets Bankers in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior South Korean
financial representative met here today with William McDonough,
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, for talks on
refinancing of the short-term debt of the Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
"It's very much informative and constructive," said Yong Hwan
Kim, co-chairman of South Korea's joint Presidential Economic
Committee, who flew in New York Sunday heading a financial
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The main issues in the talks were the form of any South Korean
debt refinancing, what prices would be acceptable to Seoul and
international bankers, and whether Seoul should issue new debt,
sources close to the South Korean delegation said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came before the South Korean representative's
meeting with leading international bankers at Citibank's New York
headquarters this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Yong is expected to outline his reaction to options drawn up
during debt refinancing talks in New York two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, global lenders agreed to roll over South Korea's
maturing obligations for 90 days, easing concerns the Asian nation
might default on some 40 billion U.S. dollars in debt coming due
by March 31.
</P>
<P>
Global lenders involved in the talks are to include most of
those who met with South Korean officials two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Citibank, the banks include Chase Manhattan, the
No. 1 bank of the nation, J.P. Morgan, Banca Commerciale Italiana,
Bank of America and Bank Tokyo-Mitsubishi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
