<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Impact of Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all ended lower today, depressed by worries over the impact the
Asian financial crisis may have on US and European corporate
earnings.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares battled back from
session lows despite sharp losses in New York during the afternoon
and ended slightly lower, down 5.9 points at 5,272.3.
</P>
<P>
Stocks were underpinned by improved interest rate sentiment
thanks to a fall in retail sales during December.
</P>
<P>
A buoyant futures market also protected the FTSE 100 index from
Wall Street's negative influence.
</P>
<P>
Germany's DAX-30 index ended down 25.07 points at 4,282.84.
Investors were using the weakness in Asia as an excuse to take
profits, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris closed 10.23 points lower at
2,998.11.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the dollar's weakness against the French
franc weighed on sentiment. But they were optimistic, saying that
today's drop was a natural consolidation after six consecutive
days of gains instead of a trend. 
</P>
