<HEADLINE> Officers Arrested on Charges of Protecting Drug Dealers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Forty-four police officers,
sheriff's deputies and prison guards from the Cleveland area in
the United States were arrested by the Federal Bureau of
Investigation on Wednesday on charges of taking payoffs to protect
cocaine dealers.
</P>
<P>
The dealers were actually undercover FBI agents taking part in
a sting, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
The law officers were charged with conspiracy to distribute
cocaine, which carries up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
The officers were paid as much as 3,700 dollars to provide
security for the "drug dealers" while they took part in deals,
said Van Harp, agent in charge of the FBI's Cleveland office.
</P>
<P>
Undercover agents staged 16 drug deals from November 1996 to
this month, the FBI said.
</P>
<P>
Eight other people were arrested on drug charges as part of the
sting. 
</P>
