<HEADLINE> Turkey Protests British Visa Restrictions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey lodged a protest at
Britain Wednesday for its visa requirement on the Turkish Cypriots
who used to enjoy a visa-free entry into Britain.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman
Necati Utkan said that Ankara supports the Turkish Cypriot
authorities' position on this issue.
</P>
<P>
"They (the Turkish Cypriots) have asserted their reaction and we
fully support their stance," Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
Britain announced last week to end the visa-free entry of the
holders of the travel documents of Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash said Tuesday that
Britain's move is to isolate the Turkish Cypriots, which he
described as "unjust and unfair."
</P>
<P>
But Britain rejected Denktash's criticism Wednesday, saying the
move is for immigrant concerns instead of political motive.
</P>
<P>
Almost 1,000 political asylum claims have been received from
Turkish Cypriots over the past two years, according to a senior
British representative in Nicosia, capital of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is only recognized by
Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Bosnia Sign Agreements to Enhance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 21 (xinhua) -- Turkey and Bosnia-Herzegovina
signed on Wednesday two agreements in an effort to strengthen
bilateral cooperation, semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed following talks between Turkish
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and visiting Bosian Co-Prime Ministers
Haris Silajdzic and Boro Bosic.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Bosnia will adopt necessary measures to increase
mutual protection and promotion of investments as well as
cooperation in transportation under the agreements.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Yilmaz and the Bosian leaders discussed the
procedure of Turkey's pledge to grant 80 million U.S. dollars of
economic aid to the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The sum of money, 20 million in donations and 60 million in
loans, will be used to help the country reconstruct its badly
destroyed infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two sides also exchanged views over
the obstacles thwarting the full implementation of the Dayton
peace accord signed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Turkish soldiers are participating in the
peace-Keening mission of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian delegation, which arrived here on Tuesday
evening, had held talks with Turkish President Suleyman Demirel,
Deputy Parliament Speaker Hasan Korkmazcan and Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after his meeting with the Bosian
officials, Cem said that the two sides had agreed to work
out regular working plans to further their understanding and
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Bosnia-Herzegovina is a country with which we share a
common history. Turkey will do its best to give economic
support to the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Bosian officials will leave on Thursday for Istanbul,
the largest city of Turkey, where they are expected to meet
leading Turkish businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
