<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Arrives in Washington for Mideast Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Palestinian
Authority Yasir Arafat arrived in Washington today for talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton on the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader is expected to meet Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright this evening and then hold talks with Clinton
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said in Paris on his way to Washington that he pinned
his hope on the president for the progress of the peace process,
which has almost collapsed since last March because of Israel's
decision to build Jewish housing units in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"We have great confidence in President Clinton and hope he
will get the peace process back on the rails and moving again,"
he said after his talks with French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Clinton held two rounds of talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday in an effort to revitalize the moribund
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The United States believes that further withdrawal of the
Israeli troops from a significantly sizable part of the West
Bank is important for Israel and the Palestinians to push the
peace process forward. And Clinton offered some fresh ideas for
further redeployment to Netanyahu during their talks.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu put the security on the first place and said the
Palestinians must comply with their commitment to Israel's
security before Israel could consider any ceding of its occupied
land.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said after the two meetings between Clinton
and Netanyahu that gaps between the two leaders remain and could
not be solved over night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
