<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin: United States Needs to Help Address Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Although the impact of the
Asian financial crisis on the United States is "relatively
moderate" so far, the United States needed to help pay for
international rescue deals, the Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Georgetown University, Rubin also noted the
fallout "could be much greater" if the financial problems spread
to other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to stand back and gamble that the crisis will
resolve itself,... We must do everything sensible to help address
this crisis because the alternative of doing nothing will lead
to far deeper and far longer financial instability and economic
duress," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The secretary said, "Roughly 40 percent of our exports have
been going to emerging markets around the globe."
</P>
<P>
Some of the largest U.S. exporters rely on Asia and most of
the U.S. regions have felt the impact of the Asian crisis. But
Rubin said international rescue efforts undertaken by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) appear to be containing the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Rubin added that It is "absolutely critical" that Japan shores
up its financial system and generates solid growth in order to help
Asia recover. "A strong Japan would be a source of strength for
the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration is seeking for Congress approval of
additional some 18 billion U.S. dollars to help IMF's rescue
programs, but meeting very strong opposition from some
Congressmen.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that cutting funding to the IMF would hurt U.S.
businesses and workers.
</P>
<P>
In a interview with USA Today earlier this week, the Secretary
warned a failure by Congress to approve the request for additional
funding for the IMF would be a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also called for an international meeting later this
Spring of the Group 7 leading industrial nations and others to
find new ways to cope with the kind of crises that have affected
Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
