<HEADLINE> Most Frenchmen Expect Social Crisis to Occur in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-four percent of the
Frenchmen think that a major social crisis will take place in 1998
in France, according to a poll published Wednesday by the weekly
"L'Evenement."
</P>
<P>
Only 32 percent of the Frenchmen think that a major social
crisis is unlikely, said the poll conducted by the IFOP polling
institute last week on 986 people above 18.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-four percent of the people polled think that the social
"explosion" will be triggered by the unemployed, 23 percent
think it will be created by youths in the urban suburb, and 6
percent think the students will launch protests.
</P>
<P>
People of other professions who could lead protests are truck
drivers, teachers and state employees, said the poll. 
</P>
