<HEADLINE> 10,000 Rwandans Rise Against Hutu Extremists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 21 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 people took it to
the streets of the north-western town of Gisenyi in Rwanda today
to protest the on-going bloodshed blamed on Hutu extremists,
reported the Rwanda News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn the continuing genocide," "collaborators of
terrorists should be arrested and exemplarily punished," some of
the posters held by protesters read.
</P>
<P>
The protesters had come from all over the country to bury the
victims of Monday's attack on a bus of Rwandan Brewery by Hutu
militia that left 35 dead, and 35 others wounded, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Life in Gisenyi was brought to a standstill today with
schools, public offices and businesses shut down.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that some residents from the neighboring town
of Goma of the Democratic Republic of Congo joined in the protest
in solidarity with families which lost members in the attack.
</P>
<P>
The protesters were preceded by a train of 15 coffins carrying
25 bodies of the victims which were calcinated when the bus was
set afire by the criminals.
</P>
<P>
The victims were buried this afternoon in a cemetery in
Gisenyi Town.
</P>
<P>
This morning, one man who had had his back badly burnt
succumbed to the burns which affected his lungs, bringing the
casualty figure to 36, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
But one human rights association based in Kigali, however,
indicated that the number of victims had risen to 52 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports indicated today that more bodies continued
to be found in bushes near the site of Monday's ambush, but
failed to give the number.
</P>
<P>
Monday's attack on the Rwandan Brewery bus is one of the many
incidents in which armed Hutu extremists have ambushed vehicles,
killing indiscriminately their passengers before setting them
ablaze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
