<HEADLINE> Army Chief: Israel Not to Withdraw From S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel will not pull back its
troops unilaterally from south Lebanon unless the security of
northern Israel is guaranteed, said Israel's top army officer
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops will not leave south Lebanon before any
arrangement is made for the security of the border areas between
Israel and Lebanon, Amnon Shahak, chief of staff of the Israeli
Defense Forces said at a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government recently hinted at holding negotiations
with Israel on the security arrangement for the border areas, but
no action has been taken so far, Shahak said.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, the Israeli army regards it as a positive move and will
support any such negotiations, he added.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the situation in the security zone in south
Lebanon is not satisfactory due to the resistance of Lebanese
guerrilla forces.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 1,100-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly protect its northern areas from
cross-border attacks by Lebanon's guerrilla groups. Lebanese
resistance forces have been fighting ever since to drive out the
Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
Referring the regional security situation, Shahak accused Iran,
Iraq and some other countries in the region of adopting hostile
policies toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
Iran's plan to acquire missile technology poses "a direct
threat" to Israel's security, he said, adding that Israel will
continue to develop the advanced missile system to dwarf the
threat.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the worries of other countries in the region about
the military cooperation between Israel and Turkey, Shahak said
the cooperation is not directed against any third party.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, the Israeli top military
officer said the stalled peace process has led to security
problems in the region.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the Palestinian side for not doing enough in fighting
terrorism, but he welcomed the security cooperation between Israel
and the Palestinian National authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
