<HEADLINE> Zambia Rakes 500,000 Dollars from Mine Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambia raked 500,000 Dollars
from issuing mine licenses in 1997, Mine and Minerals Development
Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye said here today.
</P>
<P>
He told a news briefing that the government raked 700 million
Kwacha (about 500,000 U.S. Dollars) from issuing 211 small scale
mine licenses and 112 large scale mine licenses last year.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the licenses are for gemstones exploration.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the explorers spend 45 million Dollars in
explorations as compared to 20 million Dollars in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the amount of money invested in the mining sector
is an indication that the sector is very attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) continues to invest
heavily in the operations and therefore its output increased to
326,000 tons in 1997 compared with 310,000 tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will address the problems that are
hindering the exploration to the full of the gemstone industry by
the small scale miners.
</P>
<P>
The problems includes lack of finance, technology, equipment
and knowledge on marketing strategies, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry will send in the next few weeks some
officials to meet the miners and tackle the issues which were
raised by the miners during the minister's tour of mines. 
</P>
