<HEADLINE> British Diplomat on Visa Issue for Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Britain's decision requiring
Turkish Cypriots to secure entry visas for Britain in Nicosia is
not a step toward recognition of the self-styled Turkish Cypriot
regime, a spokesman for the British High Commission in Cyprus said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Piers Cazalet told Cyprus News Agency that "this is a change
of procedure whereby Turkish Cypriots now have to seek entry
clearance in Nicosia, rather than at their point of entry in
Heathrow or other British airports."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was referring to a British decision last week
that it would end visa-free entry to the holders of Turkish
Cypriot travel documents after processing almost 1,000 unfounded
asylum claims over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The decision "was taken purely on immigration grounds. It is
not politically motivated whatsoever," Cazalet stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said in the past two years Britain has had about 1,000
Turkish Cypriots who applied for political asylum. "This puts an
enormous financial and administrative burden on the British
government which we can no longer bear," he added.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has reacted furiously
to the British decision, describing it as a deliberate
action.
</P>
<P>
He warned that he would refuse to see Britain's special Cyprus
envoy David Hannay unless London lifts visa requirements for
Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Cazalet noted that Britain had explained to Denktash and to
other Turkish Cypriots the reason behind the decision.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on statements by Denktash that there will be no
more intercommunal talks in Cyprus, the British diplomat said "we
fully support the search for a political settlement in Cyprus
under the U.N. auspices."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the British Foreign Office also reiterated in
London Wednesday that Britain is supporting the U.N. effort for
the solution of the Cyprus problem, and sticks to that policy.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the visa measure "is of a technical nature,
without any political importance and is aiming at controlling the
immigration problem."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed Greek Cypriot coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots set up a breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in November 1983, recognized only by
Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
