<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu-Clinton Talks Spark Different Responses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli, Palestinian
politicians reacted differently Wednesday to the talks held
between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and United
States President Bill Clinton Tuesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Hardliners of the Israeli rightwing coalition lauded Netanyahu
for resisting U.S. pressure to make compromise to the Palestinian
side.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Silvan Shalom of the Netanyahu-led
Likud Party said Netanyahu went to Washington not to give in to
U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
Knesset (parliament) members of the National Religious Party
reiterated their strong opposition to carrying out the proposed
troop pullback in the West Bank, saying Netanyahu must stand
firmly against any U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
The Council for Settlers in the Territories issued a statement
that the settlers are proud of Netanyahu for standing up to
U.S. pressure and defending the interests of the settlers.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held after his talks with Clinton,
Netanyahu claimed the talks have produced some progress but no
major breakthrough. In another speech at the National Press Club
in Washington, he defended Israel's policy of continuing to expand
Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli opposition lawmakers lashed out at Netanyahu
and the rightwing government for failing to push forward the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Decrying the lack of concrete results of the Netanyahu-Clinton
talks, Secretary of the leading opposition Labor Party Ranan Cohen
called for an urgent meeting of Knesset's Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee to discuss Netanyahu's U.S. trip.
</P>
<P>
Labor lawmaker Moshe Shahal said the Washington talks are
doomed to failure from the very start because Netanyahu's hands
have been tightly tied by his hardline coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
He also warned against the escalation of Israeli-Palestinian
conflict due to the continued deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Another opposition leader Yossi Sarid of the Meretz Party said
the failure of the Washington talks has shown that only the
convening of a David Camp-style summit will save the deeply
troubled peace process.
</P>
<P>
In its initial response, the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) criticized the U.S. government for its capitulation to
Netanyahu's intransigence.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has expressed hope that Clinton will pressure Netanyahu
to soften his tough stand and advance the peace process by
carrying out the long-delayed troop pullback.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Hasan Asfour said since the
Netanyahu-Clinton talks have failed, the Clinton administration
should step up its pressure on Israel now to make progress in the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to hold talks with PNA President Yasser
Arafat in a continued effort to narrow the huge gap between Israel
and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said that he has confidence in Clinton to save the
peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
