<HEADLINE> Technology M&AMP;A Deals up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The value of global
transactions in the technology industry rose 17 percent to 242.8
billion U.S. dollars in 1997, a U.S. firm reported.
</P>
<P>
Deals of mergers and acquisitions in the industry soared 25
percent to 4,040 in 1997 against a 21 percent jump in 1996, the
Wall Street Journal today quoted the New Jersey-based investment
banking firm Broadview Associates as saying.
</P>
<P>
U.S. companies dominated the mergers and acquisitions market
globally, accounting for two-thirds of deals.
</P>
<P>
The software sector saw a steady growth in the M&AMP;A activity,
with 1,287 deals in 1997 valued at 31.5 billion dollars, up from
989 deals valued at 22.4 billion dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The media sector also underwent a sharp increase in the number
of deals, up to 893 transactions valued at 43.1 billion dollars in
1997 from 662 valued at 35 billion dollars in 1996 and 524 valued
at 21.2 billion dollars in 1955.
</P>
<P>
Broadview found that more information technology companies
prefer M&AMP;A to public listing for funding.
</P>
<P>
A total of 202 technology firms went public in 1997 while 1,682
ones chose the M&AMP;A way. In 1996, there were 1,286 M&AMP;A deals, a
fourth of the number of public listings.
</P>
<P>
The 10 largest global transactions in the technology industry
were dominated by telecommunications and hardware deals. The most
noticeable was the merger of WorldCom with MCI communications for
37 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Broadview sees those companies developing technologies to
improve speed of data transmission, especially over the Internet,
to attract more M&AMP;A activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Seeks Closer Ties with Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- India is willing to undertake
joint ventures and cooperation with Nigeria in the fields of
telecommunications, space technology, small-scale industry, power
and energy, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
It seems that India has particular interest in cooperation in
space technology with Nigeria as its High Commissioner to
Nigeria, Satinder Uppal, has called on the west African country
to utilize India's satellite recently put in space.
</P>
<P>
Apart from that, Uppal said, his country had also set up a
ground station in South Africa for cooperation in space
technology and mapping of geological data.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Nigerian government has expressed an
intention to send a delegation to India for discussion in this
area.
</P>
<P>
Due to the traditional relations between the two former
British colonies, there are more than 24,000 Indians living in
Nigeria, the biggest foreign community from outside Africa.
</P>
<P>
They have made large investments in the textile,
pharmaceutical, plastics, agriculture, rubber, electrical and
electronics industries, providing employment for many Nigerians,
the envoy said.
</P>
<P>
About 1,000 Nigerians have been trained in India over the last
20 years in a variety of fields, he said, adding that 25 percent
or more of the military administrators in Nigeria's 36 states
today have a stint of military training in his country.
</P>
<P>
Under the "very cordial" relations, Nigeria has become India's
biggest trading partner in Africa, with about five percent of
Nigeria's export going to India.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's exports to India, mainly crude oil, put the balance
of trade advantage in Nigeria's favor, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Uppal said, Nigeria is currently Africa's second
largest importer of Indian products, mainly pharmaceuticals,
rice, machinery, equipment and vehicles from India.
</P>
<P>
"We hope in the current Indian financial year ending March 31,
our exports will be a little over 200 million U.S. Dollars," he
said, without giving any further figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
