<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Faces Massive Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran will face a budget deficit
of 20,000 billion Iranian rials (11.4 billion U.S. dollars) in
next Iranian fiscal year (to start from March 21), 150 percent
more than the predicted figure of the current year.
</P>
<P>
This prediction came in an editorial on Wednesday's English
language daily Iran News. The daily attributed this to a decrease
of hard currency revenue caused by oil price fall.
</P>
<P>
Iran's budget is usually a deficit-free one.
</P>
<P>
The daily criticized the country's reliance on oil industry as
too much, saying that "it is high time that we abandoned our high
expectations from an oil-based economy."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Parliament has cut the forecast for oil incomes for
the next fiscal year by 7.5 percent to about 13.8 billion
U.S. dollars from 14.9 billion dollars anticipated by the
government basing on an oil price of 17.5 dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament set the oil price at 16 dollars a barrel for the
budget of the new Iranian year. But Iranian crude oil is traded
around 12 dollars at present. Officials believe that the country
can not fetch the projected oil incomes in the new year since oil
prices are not expected to rise.
</P>
<P>
Government officials have urged the Parliament to take
immediate measures to deal with the shortage of money in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Iran had expected 17.7 billion dollars oil revenues in the
current Iranian year basing on an average price of 17.5 dollars a
barrel of Iranian crude oil.
</P>
<P>
But it only earned 10 billion dollars in the first eight months
of the year. Experts said that the total oil revenue would be
around 15 billion dollars with the current oil price, 15.25
percent below the projected figure.
</P>
<P>
At present, Iran exports about 2.5 million barrels per day
(bpd), earning about 80 percent of the country's badly-needed
hard currency.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil production ceiling was raised by 340,000
million bpd to 3.94 million bpd this year according to a decision
by the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries in last
November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
