<HEADLINE> Planes in Nigeria Warned Not to Take Off or Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Airline operators in Nigeria
have been told to stop taking off or landing in bad weather,
especially in the northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Any aircraft which violated the internationally accepted
minimum standard for visibility for landing and taking off shall
be grounded, Minister of Aviation Air Commodore ITA Udo-Imeh
warned.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has since the beginning of this year witnessed poor
visibility caused by thick haze of the Harmattan, a seasonal dry,
dust-laden wind coming from the Sahara up in the north.
</P>
<P>
Scores of air travelers on domestic routes were stranded at
some airports across the country. But there is yet no report on
the interruption of international flights because of weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Nigeria has suffered adverse
consequences of past violations of the standard prescribed by the
International Civil Aviation organization.
</P>
<P>
Lives and material resources were wasted because of
carelessness, he said, adding that his ministry was doing
everything possible to ensure an accident-free year this year.
</P>
<P>
An air tragedy two years ago claimed the life of the eldest
son of the Nigerian Head of State, General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Britain banned Nigerian aircraft from entering its airspace
last May over alleged lack of safety from the Nigerian part,
inviting retaliation from Nigeria with a ban on British aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The face-off remains though Britain lifted the ban three
months later. Negotiations have been reportedly begun between the
two countries to iron out the dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
