<HEADLINE> More Americans Willing to Donate Organs: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Americans are increasingly
designating themselves as organ donors, a survey found.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based National Kidney Foundation (NKF), which
released the survey report today, said 55 percent of whites
surveyed and one third of blacks and Hispanics plan to be organ
donors.
</P>
<P>
These numbers are up from one third and one quarter
respectively in 1992 when NKF conducted a similar opinion poll.
</P>
<P>
The latest survey of 1,200 randomly selected individuals also
shows that people with children are slightly more likely to be
organ donors than those with no children under 19.
</P>
<P>
A poll of transplant recipients and physicians indicated a high
level of support for anumal-to-human transplantation or
xenotransplantation among these groups, NKF said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Americans are aware of the shortage of available
organs for transplant and accept the concept of
zenotransplantation.
</P>
<P>
There are about 53,000 Americans currently awaiting life-saving
transplants and ten people dying each day while waiting.
</P>
<P>
However, it was found that at least half of the transplant
physicians surveyed are willing to give xenotransplantation 10
years or more before it is required to show success, NKF said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
