<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Sends Farming Inputs for Coming Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural inputs needed
for this year's harvest seasons are being distributed to the
various regions in the country, the Agricultural Inputs Supply
Enterprise of Ethiopia announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Manager of the enterprise Sewinet Tizazu told local
journalists that the enterprise has so far procured 140,000 tons
of fertilizers as part of its plan to import 230,000 tons this
year.
</P>
<P>
The fertilizer is being distributed to areas that produce in
the small rainy season from February to May, Sewinet said, adding
that it has been transported to the northern Amhara and Tigray
regions directly from the port.
</P>
<P>
She said, the fertilizer to be utilized for the year would
reach the hinterland until the end of February.
</P>
<P>
The enterprise will supply 75 percent of the 360,000 tons of
fertilizer the country needs and the remaining will be procured
by private importers, she added.
</P>
<P>
According to the manager, the enterprise has earmarked 600
million Birr (about 87 million U.S. Dollars) for the purchase of
agricultural inputs this year.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia had a record crop harvest of 11.7 million tons in
1996. However, crop production sharply declined last year due to
drought and untimely rains in some parts of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
