<HEADLINE> Turkey's Constitutional Court Supports Closure of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Constitutional Court
Wednesday rejected an appeal for the cancellation of the law which
orders the closure of casinos by February 11, semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The high court turned down the application, filed by certain
civil courts for the annulment of an article in the law no. 4320,
amending the Law on Encouragement of Tourism.
</P>
<P>
Judge Guven Dincer said in a statement following the court
session that the unconstitutional claim was rejected by a vote of
nine to two.
</P>
<P>
In their application, the local courts maintained that the law
did not conform with the principles of equality and was against
the freedom of labor.
</P>
<P>
According to the controversial law, which was officially
published on August 10, 1997, the activities of casinos should
come to a halt in a six-month period after the law's
publication. 
