<HEADLINE> EU Urges Europe to Catch Up in Satellite Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today urged Europe to catch
up in the race to develop and exploit state-of-art global
navigation satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive today approved a strategic plan to ensure a
full European role in the development of Global Navigation
Satellite Systems (GNSS).
</P>
<P>
"The market is developing so fast that we need to develop now a
strategy for the future. In this technology, late in will mean
Europe is locked out of a market estimated to be worth 50 billion
dollars by 2005," said EU Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the EU still needed to decide whether to do it
alone or to cooperate with its international partners and that
cooperation under right conditions should be greatly preferred.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said the plan was aimed at a full European
role in system development and operation, guarantees of adequate
control of satellite signals and the opportunity for European
industry to compete on equal terms.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of today's decision, the commission will ask the
European Council of Transport Ministers and the European
Parliament to endorse this strategic plan.
</P>
<P>
Satellite navigations systems can be used to track dangerous
goods, identify fishing grounds, locate ship wrecks, enhance air
traffic control, guide blind people or advise drivers about
hazardous or congested roads.
</P>
<P>
But the two existing global systems -- GPS and GLONASS -- were
developed for military purposes and remain under the control of
the United States and Russia respectively.
</P>
<P>
A European system known as EGNOS, under development by the
European Space Agency and the air traffic control management
center Eurocontrol, is set to be in operation from 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
