<HEADLINE> 637 Ethiopian Refugees Return from Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Over 630 Ethiopian
refugees who had been in neighboring Sudan for years due to the
then ravaging war and droughts in their homeland, have returned
home.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today from Humera,
Ethiopia's north-western town near its border with Sudan, the
returnees, after a day's stay in Humera, have been transported to
camps in Gondar and Endasellassie in the north.
</P>
<P>
The transport was carried out with the support of the
Organization for Rehabilitation and Development in Amhara region,
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and the
Administration for Refugees and Returnees Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Each refugee family will receive 1,000 Birr (about 145 U.S.
Dollars), nine-month ration, blanket and utensils before leaving
for their respective localities, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,500 Ethiopian refugees have returned to their homeland
from Sudan through Humera since December 15, 1997. The Ethiopian
government has plans to repatriate some 20,000 refugees from
Sudan until May, 1998 with the assistance from the UNHCR.
</P>
