<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Brings Impact to Most Regions of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Most regions of the United
States now are feeling the impact of Asia's financial and economic
crisis, with the U.S. manufacturers reporting weakened demand from
Asia, the Federal Reserve said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The impact of Asian financial turmoil was felt in most
districts," the Federal Reserve noted in its survey of economic
conditions by its 12 regional banks. "Manufacturers and
agricultural firms report weaker exports to Asia, and there is
some evidence of increased competition from Asian products in U.S.
markets."
</P>
<P>
The latest report, based on information collected through
January 11, indicates more widespread effects from the Asian
currency crises than the previous survey, released on January 3,
which had the first anecdotal hints of fallout.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian financial turmoil started to have some impact on
manufacturing activity," the latest report said. "Some districts
reported weaker export demand for industrial equipment, building
materials, aircraft parts, semiconductors, processed food and some
metals."
</P>
<P>
However, the Fed also said, "the pace of economic growth
continued to be moderate" and "labor markets remained tight or
very tight in all districts."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that qualified workers are in such short supply
in some fields, including computer-related workers, skilled
construction workers and technicians, that some firms scaled back
production or expansion plans, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
"A company in Nashville was forced to idle more than 10 percent
of its equipment due to labor shortages. In the Chicago district,
some projects were canceled due to a lack of labor, while in the
St. Louis district some contacts were unable to meet production
schedules," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The shortages are resulting in some upward pressure on wages,
but "prices were generally flat due to intense competition and
lower import prices."
</P>
<P>
Rising wages for retail jobs were noted in the Boston and
Richmond regions, while Boston said manufacturers were offering
double-digit increases to engineers.
</P>
<P>
"Most districts suggested that employers continued to be
creative in finding and recruiting additional labor," the report
said. "Some companies were subsidizing transportation for
employees located far away from work sites. Employers in several
districts adopted flexible work schedules and more generous
benefit packages." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
