The Commission said in a statement Wednesday that as the first
step, it would allow job seekers up to age 45 to sit for exams for
the basic civil service grades. The age limit used to be 32 or
35.
</P>
<P>
Noting that its age restrictions have been accused of being
"discriminatory and arbitrary", the Commission said it was going
to use the increased power given by new amendments to the EU
treaty to fight age discriminations.
</P>
<P>
"The European Commission today approved in principle ending of
age limits for admission to its competitions for recruitment," it
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
However, it also said that it would do it gradually and in
coordination with other EU institutions.
</P>
<P>
Erkki Liikanen, EU commissioner responsible for personnel
matters, has been leading the efforts to completely end the age
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
But other officials have expressed concern about issues such as
career development, pension plans and recruitment policy, said his
spokeswoman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980122.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-21 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 86 Plane Accidents Occur in Turkey Over 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- There have been 86 plane
accidents in Turkey over the last five years, killing a total of
81 people, said a Transportation Ministry report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 49 out of 86 plane accidents were a result
of pilot errors and the highest accident rate was experienced in
1995.
</P>
<P>
It said that there were 15 plane accidents in 1993, 14 in 1994,
24 in 1995, 20 in 1996 and 13 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The highest number of fatalities occurred in an accident in
eastern province of Van linking Iran in 1994 when 56 people were
killed and the pilot was found to be responsible for the crash,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It added that technical and weather reasons were other causes
of the aircraft accidents.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-eight of the planes involved in the 86 crash incidents
belonged to official institutions, while the other 58 were private
planes, the report pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
