<HEADLINE> Blair Ready to Make Statement on Bloody Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said today he would respond soon to demands for an inquiry
into the "Bloody Sunday" killing.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the parliament during the question time, Blair
said, "We have a duty to address that."
</P>
<P>
On January 30, 1972, 14 Northern Irish Catholics were killed by
British troops in Londonderry while staging a protest march.
</P>
<P>
The Irish government and relatives of the victims have been
pressing the British government to apologize and agree to a fresh
inquiry into the killings by the British soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"The mass of material prepared by the Irish government has
required thorough investigation by more than one government
department. We hope to be in a position to make a statement on it
soon," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"We are investigating all the evidence very carefully and will
make a judgment based on the facts," he said.
</P>
<P>
At least 12 other civilians were wounded in the Bloody Sunday
conflict. 
</P>
