<HEADLINE> Iraq Confident of Technical Evaluation Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz said Wednesday that he has strong confidence that the
results of the forthcoming technical evaluation meetings will be
in favor of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made the remarks at a news conference after his talks with
United Nations chief arms inspector Richard Butler who has
left here for Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Aziz proposed a freeze on the discussion of
the access to the presidential palaces and other sensitive sites
of the U.N. arms inspectors until the results of technical
meetings, which are scheduled to be held on February 1, come out.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the participation of arms experts from the five
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council or other countries
in the inspection will help both sides to reach conclusion about
"where we stand."
</P>
<P>
He said Russia and France will increase the number of experts
for the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), and that China has
decided for the first time to join the mission of the UNSCOM,
which he described as good development to make the composition of
the UNSCOM balanced.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been accusing the Americans and the Britons of
dominating the work of the UNSCOM, which is responsible for
verifying the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that 112 visits have been made by the arms inspectors
in the past 19 months to sensitive sites, during which they have
used very sophisticated instruments, but have not found any
prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the main reason that UNSCOM's inspectors
want to enter the presidential sites is for espionage, not for
disarmament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
