<HEADLINE> Angolan Air Force Jets Force down UNITA Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 21 (Xinhua) -- A South African airplane was
forced down near Menongue, a city in southwestern Angola Tuesday
by the Angolan air force for transporting cargo for the former
rebel UNITA movement, an air force official said today.
</P>
<P>
Francisco Lopes, the official in charge of operation in
Angola's air force, told a press conference in Menongue that
Angola's fighter jets and bombers had to confront the plane which
had intruded into the country's southwestern territorial space at
11:00 GMT Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations indicated that the private plane
had been transporting cargo for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Peter Bitzker, the 37-year-old pilot for the South African
plane, told Xinhua that he was a pilot for private planes and had
been working for many companies.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, he said, he had flown many times to
transport cargo and ammunition for UNITA. Only six months ago,
he had flown weapons for UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The plane had flown form South Africa via Botswana to Andulo,
a central Angolan city where one of UNITA's headquarters is
located. When it was forced down by the air force, it was merely
200 km away from the destination.
</P>
<P>
The eight people on board the plane include three crew members
and five passengers. One of them disclosed that there were
military coaches among them who are expected to train UNITA
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the eight people have been detained in a
military camp near Luanda for further interrogation.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. security Council passed a resolution in October 1997
to impose sanctions on the former rebel movement. However, there
were still reports of violations of the embargo, over which the
Angolan government has expressed its indignation, said Lopes.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the Angolan air force stopped and
forced down such planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
