<HEADLINE> IBM's Shares Drop Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 21 (Xinhua) -- The stock of the International
Business Machines Corp (IBM) dropped 7 percent today after the
computer giant warned that its fourth-quarter profit would fall
short because of the continued negative impact of a strong dollar,
weak Asia markets and several one-time expenses.
</P>
<P>
IBM shares were down 7.75 U.S. dollars a share, or 7.2 percent,
in early afternoon trading. It was the investor's first chance to
react to the financial warning, issued after the close of the
markets Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The IBM's warning also led Dow Jones industrial average down
today. At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow average was down 108.36
at 7,764.76, nearly wiping out Tuesday's 119-point climb.
</P>
<P>
IBM's 1997 fourth-quarter net income rose to 2.1 billion
dollars, or 2.11 dollars per diluted share, just below analyst
estimates. Revenue was 23.7 billion U.S. dollars, up 3 percent
from 23.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from Asia was flat at 4.4 billion U.S. dollars. If not
for the Asia crisis, revenue would have risen 10 percent, IBM
says.
</P>
<P>
For all of 1997, IBM earned 6.1 billion U.S. dollars on 78.5
billion U.S. dollars in revenue, up 3.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
